58:25.980 --> 58:27.140
Like there's really not a,

58:27.140 --> 58:29.780
we end up using those words colloquially, right?

58:29.780 --> 58:32.580
Which is why, you know, concepts that we can define,

58:32.580 --> 58:36.540
like envy, empathic attunement, narcissism,

58:36.540 --> 58:38.780
even though there might be nuances and definitions,

58:38.780 --> 58:42.620
like we can define them in ways that are widely accepted,

58:42.660 --> 58:45.420
including within psychology and psychiatry.

58:45.420 --> 58:46.980
So it's nice to just think about this

58:46.980 --> 58:48.420
a broad umbrella of narcissism

58:48.420 --> 58:52.060
and the levels to which it's benign or malignant,

58:52.060 --> 58:55.580
and then also separating into the different mechanisms,

58:55.580 --> 58:57.380
like interaction by interaction,

58:57.380 --> 58:58.940
which sometimes can be narcissistic,

58:58.940 --> 59:00.460
but broadly speaking,

59:00.460 --> 59:03.300
do you do everything through the lens of malignant narcissism

59:03.300 --> 59:08.300
that makes you a sociopath or a malignant narcissist?

59:09.300 --> 59:10.860
Yes, and the thing I would add to that

59:10.860 --> 59:12.420
is the thought about culture, right?

59:12.540 --> 59:14.340
Like how does the cultures we're in,

59:14.340 --> 59:16.500
whether it's the culture of a household, right?

59:16.500 --> 59:17.660
The culture of a community,

59:17.660 --> 59:19.780
the culture of a nation or the world, right?

59:19.780 --> 59:23.900
How does that impact what unfolds in that person?

59:23.900 --> 59:26.260
And then how does what unfolds in that person

59:26.260 --> 59:27.380
impact that culture?

59:27.380 --> 59:30.580
Well, that's the question is what unfolds in that person?

59:31.660 --> 59:33.220
Yeah, how does culture affect it?

59:33.220 --> 59:37.820
But how does your own psychological development unfold that?

59:37.820 --> 59:42.060
Because narcissism in leaders is the most impactful thing,

59:42.900 --> 59:45.220
who are the most impactful individuals?

59:45.220 --> 59:47.780
What is the most impact of individual psychology we have?

59:47.780 --> 59:49.940
It's usually leaders of countries

59:49.940 --> 59:52.580
or leaders of major organizations and so on.

59:52.580 --> 59:56.220
And one of the things you mentioned with benign narcissism,

59:56.220 --> 59:59.540
that seems to be aligned with success, right?

59:59.540 --> 01:00:01.780
If you care about your own success,

01:00:01.780 --> 01:00:03.700
that's going to be,

01:00:03.700 --> 01:00:06.660
you're more likely to have narcissistic tendencies,

01:00:06.660 --> 01:00:07.500
I suppose.

01:00:07.900 --> 01:00:10.700
And so my question is,

01:00:10.700 --> 01:00:14.140
when you follow that thread of narcissism

01:00:14.140 --> 01:00:16.780
to become the leader of a country,

01:00:16.780 --> 01:00:20.620
now you have a lot of new interesting

01:00:20.620 --> 01:00:24.060
psychological complexities to deal with, like power.

01:00:24.060 --> 01:00:26.100
I don't cliche that power corrupts.

01:00:27.100 --> 01:00:31.820
Does that, is it possible for power to corrupt a human mind?

01:00:31.820 --> 01:00:35.180
To where it pushes you farther and farther

01:00:35.180 --> 01:00:38.260
into malignant narcissism,

01:00:38.260 --> 01:00:40.500
into this destructive envy.

01:00:40.500 --> 01:00:42.180
What are your thoughts on power?

01:00:42.180 --> 01:00:44.540
Like the effect of power in the human mind?

01:00:44.540 --> 01:00:49.540
Yeah, I think power is an accentuator, right?

01:00:50.700 --> 01:00:52.460
An intensifier, right?

01:00:52.460 --> 01:00:57.460
So I think it is true that there are people who can be

01:00:57.500 --> 01:00:59.340
sort of in a gray area where there are

01:00:59.340 --> 01:01:04.060
malignant narcissistic tendencies and behaviors,

01:01:04.060 --> 01:01:06.340
but there are also ways in which that person

01:01:06.340 --> 01:01:07.700
can think outside of themselves

01:01:07.700 --> 01:01:08.940
and think in a broader way

01:01:08.940 --> 01:01:11.260
and think sort of kindly about others.

01:01:11.260 --> 01:01:14.900
And they're sort of trying to navigate,

01:01:14.900 --> 01:01:15.980
whether they're aware or not,

01:01:15.980 --> 01:01:17.100
that they're trying to navigate

01:01:17.100 --> 01:01:18.140
between one and the other.

01:01:18.140 --> 01:01:20.020
And then the allure of power is,

01:01:20.020 --> 01:01:21.700
well, just look, just exercise that power

01:01:21.700 --> 01:01:23.020
and you'll feel better, right?

01:01:23.020 --> 01:01:24.780
It'll show you, right, that you're good enough.

01:01:24.780 --> 01:01:25.820
Look at the power you have.

01:01:25.820 --> 01:01:28.460
And whatever may be going on in the person's mind,

01:01:28.460 --> 01:01:32.340
that then power, yes, can corrupt, yes.

01:01:32.340 --> 01:01:35.060
I think that's why we have to have checks and balances, right?

01:01:35.060 --> 01:01:38.620
Because we are all inscrutable to ourselves,

01:01:38.620 --> 01:01:39.580
let alone to others.

01:01:39.580 --> 01:01:41.900
So we must have checks and balances

01:01:41.900 --> 01:01:44.060
and we should always have them on ourselves

01:01:44.060 --> 01:01:45.180
as well as on others.

01:01:45.180 --> 01:01:47.460
We should want that for the health of ourselves

01:01:47.460 --> 01:01:49.480
and the world around us.

01:01:49.480 --> 01:01:51.820
So I think all of that is true,

01:01:51.820 --> 01:01:54.500
but there are also people who don't necessarily

01:01:54.500 --> 01:01:57.460
become corrupted by power, right?

01:01:57.460 --> 01:02:00.100
That there can be an understanding and a grounding

01:02:00.100 --> 01:02:02.820
that they're a steward of power, right?

01:02:02.820 --> 01:02:06.100
A shepherd, I mean, there are ways people describe

01:02:06.100 --> 01:02:10.180
utilizing power and utilizing it in a benign way

01:02:10.180 --> 01:02:14.980
that then fosters the healthy aspects of self, right?

01:02:14.980 --> 01:02:17.340
So like gratitude and humility, right?

01:02:17.340 --> 01:02:21.460
If we could add a healthy dose of gratitude and humility

01:02:21.460 --> 01:02:23.380
to everyone or to our society,

01:02:23.380 --> 01:02:24.940
there would be a sea change, right?

01:02:24.940 --> 01:02:26.560
But how do you feel gratitude?

01:02:26.560 --> 01:02:28.060
How do you feel humility?

01:02:28.100 --> 01:02:32.340
Those things are incompatible with narcissism, envy, right?

01:02:32.340 --> 01:02:35.260
With really the bad pole of things that we're talking about.

01:02:35.260 --> 01:02:38.620
And part of the reason I'm so focused in my work

01:02:38.620 --> 01:02:41.820
and in really what runs through all of my thoughts about life

01:02:41.820 --> 01:02:43.540
is the impact of trauma, right?

01:02:43.540 --> 01:02:46.300
Because trauma creates these false lessons

01:02:46.300 --> 01:02:47.940
and it walls us off from truth.

01:02:47.940 --> 01:02:52.940
Then it starts to point towards the unhealthy ways

01:02:52.940 --> 01:02:57.060
of trying to feel better about ourselves.

01:02:57.060 --> 01:03:00.180
But we have the health in us too.

01:03:00.180 --> 01:03:01.860
We have those seeds of health too

01:03:01.860 --> 01:03:04.140
that can grow into being a steward of power

01:03:04.140 --> 01:03:06.540
and sharing power, being considerate and kind.

01:03:06.540 --> 01:03:09.420
And we see a lot of that in the world too, right?

01:03:09.420 --> 01:03:11.420
It's not all just the evil.

01:03:11.420 --> 01:03:13.620
We see plenty of people who do good

01:03:13.620 --> 01:03:14.980
and who are generous of spirit.

01:03:14.980 --> 01:03:17.340
And we have both in us and it is,

01:03:17.340 --> 01:03:19.540
as I think you're talking about our culture

01:03:19.540 --> 01:03:20.860
and what the seeds that we sow

01:03:20.860 --> 01:03:23.420
and the climate that we set,

01:03:23.420 --> 01:03:25.620
including putting governors and boundaries around like,

01:03:26.180 --> 01:03:29.300
how do we reign in or say that the more aggressive,

01:03:29.300 --> 01:03:32.300
the more envious or destructive is unacceptable, right?

01:03:32.300 --> 01:03:35.380
How do we foster the part that's kind

01:03:35.380 --> 01:03:38.620
and considerate and reflective and slow to judge of like,

01:03:38.620 --> 01:03:39.740
hey, let's learn a little bit more.

01:03:39.740 --> 01:03:40.980
Like, how do we foster that?

01:03:40.980 --> 01:03:43.100
And I think a lot of that comes back

01:03:43.100 --> 01:03:44.540
to early childhood education.

01:03:44.540 --> 01:03:46.100
I mean, I think we don't do nearly enough

01:03:46.100 --> 01:03:48.020
to protect children.

01:03:48.020 --> 01:03:50.140
And as a corollary to that,

01:03:50.140 --> 01:03:52.460
we don't do nearly enough to educate children.

01:03:52.460 --> 01:03:54.020
I mean, I said, I wanna write a book.

01:03:54.020 --> 01:03:56.100
Second book I write is gonna be everything

01:03:56.100 --> 01:03:58.260
I needed to know about life.

01:03:58.260 --> 01:04:02.060
I learned as a second year postgraduate psychiatry resident.

01:04:02.060 --> 01:04:03.700
I was like, why?

01:04:03.700 --> 01:04:08.220
Why then did I learn so much about unconscious motivation,

01:04:08.220 --> 01:04:09.900
about the impact of trauma,

01:04:09.900 --> 01:04:13.180
about how we can be envious and how we can act out,

01:04:13.180 --> 01:04:15.900
even about how our emotions trump logic in us.

01:04:15.900 --> 01:04:19.660
Like, why don't we teach these things

01:04:19.660 --> 01:04:21.340
when we're young enough to understand?

01:04:21.340 --> 01:04:23.820
Like, why is that other kid bullying me, right?

01:04:23.820 --> 01:04:26.460
Or why, just because I'm a little bit bigger,

01:04:26.460 --> 01:04:28.820
do I wanna go thump that other kid on the head?

01:04:28.820 --> 01:04:31.140
Like, what's going on?

01:04:31.140 --> 01:04:33.380
That we don't do those things, you know?

01:04:33.380 --> 01:04:35.540
We're just tripping ahead of ourselves

01:04:35.540 --> 01:04:38.820
and we don't stop and think, how are we using our resources?

01:04:38.820 --> 01:04:42.180
How are we shepherding forward the next generation,

01:04:42.180 --> 01:04:43.260
which by the way is a generation

01:04:43.260 --> 01:04:44.980
that's gonna determine our fates too, right?

01:04:44.980 --> 01:04:48.620
As we get older, but we don't, you know, do that.

01:04:48.620 --> 01:04:50.020
I often think of like in the Olympics,

01:04:50.020 --> 01:04:52.620
you know, you see like the great sprinters, right?

01:04:52.620 --> 01:04:54.580
They've gotta come out of the blocks perfectly, right?

01:04:54.580 --> 01:04:56.460
So if they come out of the blocks a little bit too fast,

01:04:56.460 --> 01:04:57.460
they're gonna fall over, right?

01:04:57.460 --> 01:04:58.540
They're gonna just fall forward.

01:04:58.540 --> 01:05:03.420
And I often see that in my head about us as humans

01:05:03.420 --> 01:05:06.220
and as a culture that we're rushing so far forward.

01:05:06.220 --> 01:05:09.340
We don't stop and say, wait, let's keep the basics here.

01:05:09.340 --> 01:05:10.660
The basic techniques of like,

01:05:10.660 --> 01:05:13.660
how are we navigating forward in life?

01:05:13.660 --> 01:05:14.940
Or do we just throw all those away?

01:05:14.940 --> 01:05:18.820
Because I can get some benefit by saying that you're bad,

01:05:18.820 --> 01:05:21.620
even though what's being leveled against you is wrong, right?

01:05:21.620 --> 01:05:23.780
Like why do I take that?

01:05:23.780 --> 01:05:26.540
Or do I say, no, there's something more important here

01:05:26.540 --> 01:05:29.020
that we wanna shepherd forward in ourselves as a culture.

01:05:29.020 --> 01:05:31.640
And I think preventing childhood trauma

01:05:31.640 --> 01:05:34.300
and changing the ways that we educate children and adults

01:05:34.300 --> 01:05:37.020
would could again, make a sea change

01:05:37.020 --> 01:05:40.900
and maybe set us on a course towards a greater likelihood

01:05:40.900 --> 01:05:42.540
of survival as a species.

01:05:42.540 --> 01:05:47.540
Yeah, so talking to like people in elementary school

01:05:48.420 --> 01:05:51.860
about human nature and teaching them

01:05:51.860 --> 01:05:55.500
is so how people can be resentful and envious

01:05:55.500 --> 01:06:00.500
and how to deal with your emotions, how to, yeah.

01:06:00.500 --> 01:06:03.460
So these basic interaction things about human relationships,

01:06:03.460 --> 01:06:07.220
about friendships, about betrayal, about love,

01:06:07.220 --> 01:06:08.580
about all those things.

01:06:08.580 --> 01:06:12.660
Like it just, it's actually strange that we don't,

01:06:12.660 --> 01:06:16.660
we kind of hope the parents talk about that kind of stuff,

01:06:16.660 --> 01:06:21.660
but then the parents often need therapy themselves.

01:06:22.780 --> 01:06:24.580
The parents didn't learn it, right?

01:06:24.580 --> 01:06:25.420
Yeah, the parents didn't learn it.

01:06:25.420 --> 01:06:28.100
I mean, I'm not joking that I was mad,

01:06:28.100 --> 01:06:30.140
second year after medical school, like how is it?

01:06:30.140 --> 01:06:33.980
Like I think of things in my own life and how I,

01:06:33.980 --> 01:06:36.340
how much shame I felt after my brother's suicide.

01:06:36.340 --> 01:06:38.180
Like I was already an adult, right?

01:06:38.180 --> 01:06:41.140
I was a young adult, but I felt so much shame.

01:06:41.140 --> 01:06:43.820
I didn't, like I had no understanding that,

01:06:44.060 --> 01:06:47.660
oh, like it's a reflex to trauma, right?

01:06:47.660 --> 01:06:49.100
To feel guilt and shame.

01:06:49.100 --> 01:06:51.260
And that of course I was feeling that.

01:06:51.260 --> 01:06:54.340
It didn't mean it was true because I felt it,

01:06:54.340 --> 01:06:56.460
but I mapped the fact that I felt ashamed

01:06:56.460 --> 01:06:59.020
to the fact that I should have felt guilty and ashamed.

01:06:59.020 --> 01:07:02.020
And I like led to some very negative things in my life

01:07:02.020 --> 01:07:03.820
that I had to sort of pull myself back from

01:07:03.820 --> 01:07:04.660
and recover from.

01:07:04.660 --> 01:07:07.780
And like, I didn't know that, right?

01:07:07.780 --> 01:07:10.660
I didn't know the automaticity of the reflex

01:07:10.660 --> 01:07:11.820
and how pervasive it can be

01:07:11.820 --> 01:07:13.220
and how it can put blinders on us.

01:07:13.220 --> 01:07:15.420
And I mean, it's just one example,

01:07:15.420 --> 01:07:16.820
but you know, it's an example of something big

01:07:16.820 --> 01:07:19.860
that happens to people that we don't learn about.

01:07:19.860 --> 01:07:22.740
And I find myself sometimes having conversations

01:07:22.740 --> 01:07:23.580
with a person.

01:07:23.580 --> 01:07:26.120
I still do a lot of clinical care of having conversations

01:07:26.120 --> 01:07:28.380
with a person after a tragedy.

01:07:28.380 --> 01:07:30.060
And I'm saying, I can't believe, right?

01:07:30.060 --> 01:07:32.300
Again, I'm saying the things that this person

01:07:32.300 --> 01:07:34.220
didn't learn in elementary school

01:07:34.220 --> 01:07:35.800
because like none of us did, right?

01:07:35.800 --> 01:07:37.740
And then look at the misery and the suffering.

01:07:37.740 --> 01:07:39.020
And then I think this is one person

01:07:39.020 --> 01:07:41.180
among how many millions among us

01:07:41.180 --> 01:07:44.060
who try and go about their way

01:07:44.060 --> 01:07:46.620
without knowing things that are easily knowable

01:07:46.620 --> 01:07:47.940
because they don't even know that they're knowable

01:07:47.940 --> 01:07:50.540
because we don't teach them to ourselves.

01:07:50.540 --> 01:07:52.660
So how to deal with trauma.

01:07:52.660 --> 01:07:54.580
That trauma happens, first of all,

01:07:55.620 --> 01:07:58.420
that suffering can happen.

01:07:58.420 --> 01:08:02.700
And small trauma and big trauma, all of it can happen.

01:08:02.700 --> 01:08:05.100
And there's natural ways to deal with it.

01:08:05.100 --> 01:08:08.580
So in the case of trauma, as you write about,

01:08:08.580 --> 01:08:10.940
and we can also just talk about

01:08:10.940 --> 01:08:12.260
some more of the details of that,

01:08:12.260 --> 01:08:14.980
but it's good to bring it to the surface,

01:08:14.980 --> 01:08:19.300
to talk about it, to not be ashamed to hide it inside,

01:08:19.300 --> 01:08:22.220
to be some kind of secret that it's actually,

01:08:24.180 --> 01:08:26.220
I mean, there's a lot of positive things to say here,

01:08:26.220 --> 01:08:27.340
at least from my perspective.

01:08:27.340 --> 01:08:30.340
One is it's discussing trauma and dealing with trauma

01:08:30.340 --> 01:08:32.860
together with other human beings by talking about it.

01:08:32.860 --> 01:08:35.220
There's a path to deep friendship and intimacy

01:08:35.220 --> 01:08:36.240
with those people.

01:08:37.240 --> 01:08:41.440
There's a dark aspect to trauma, to war,

01:08:41.440 --> 01:08:46.440
that communicating it or sharing it bonds you.

01:08:47.440 --> 01:08:50.840
So like the other side of trauma is like love,

01:08:50.840 --> 01:08:54.040
is you need that hardship, not you don't need it,

01:08:54.040 --> 01:08:56.560
but hardship and trauma can often be a catalyst

01:08:56.560 --> 01:08:58.000
for a deep human connection.

01:08:58.000 --> 01:08:59.160
If you bring it to the surface,

01:08:59.160 --> 01:09:02.200
it's supposed to kind of hide it on the inside.

01:09:02.200 --> 01:09:03.800
I mean, if we can just linger on it

01:09:03.840 --> 01:09:08.160
because you've been through a few very traumatic events

01:09:08.160 --> 01:09:10.840
in your life, when you were 25 years old,

01:09:10.840 --> 01:09:13.620
as you mentioned, your brother committed suicide,

01:09:15.280 --> 01:09:17.720
what did that event teach you about life,

01:09:17.720 --> 01:09:21.760
about death and about the human mind?

01:09:23.400 --> 01:09:25.240
What certainly brought me face to face

01:09:25.240 --> 01:09:28.800
with the truths of life and death,

01:09:28.800 --> 01:09:33.440
because I had not had a major trauma before then,

01:09:33.440 --> 01:09:35.560
so there wasn't a major trauma sort of in my

01:09:35.560 --> 01:09:39.160
developmental years, that what can carry forward

01:09:39.160 --> 01:09:40.960
is a sort of omnipotence defense, right?

01:09:40.960 --> 01:09:43.040
I mean, the thought is that when we're toddlers,

01:09:43.040 --> 01:09:45.120
we all have like an omnipotence defense,

01:09:45.120 --> 01:09:47.680
which is like, I can just try and get up and run and move,

01:09:47.680 --> 01:09:49.960
and if I run into something, I'll get up and do it again,

01:09:49.960 --> 01:09:52.560
right, that we kind of have to,

01:09:52.560 --> 01:09:54.520
and it's partly the protection of the parent, et cetera,

01:09:54.520 --> 01:09:56.400
but we think we can get out there in the world

01:09:56.400 --> 01:09:57.600
and do things and we just do.

01:09:57.600 --> 01:10:00.200
And if we don't have major traumas,

01:10:00.200 --> 01:10:01.800
we can sort of carry through that,

01:10:01.800 --> 01:10:04.320
oh, like bad things aren't gonna happen to me, you know?

01:10:04.320 --> 01:10:05.880
Like, I know that they're there

01:10:05.880 --> 01:10:06.840
and I know they happen to people,

01:10:06.840 --> 01:10:09.000
but they don't happen to me, right?

01:10:09.000 --> 01:10:12.000
And sometimes what will happen is being confronted

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:15.440
with such a tragedy wipes that away very, very quickly,

01:10:15.440 --> 01:10:18.280
and then that person feels extremely exposed,

01:10:18.280 --> 01:10:22.640
like, oh, I thought that I was gonna be okay,

01:10:22.640 --> 01:10:24.560
and now I know that I'm not,

01:10:24.560 --> 01:10:26.360
and then, and that can start to lead to,

01:10:26.360 --> 01:10:27.200
and what does that mean?

01:10:27.200 --> 01:10:30.480
And now, is this all coming for me now, you know?

01:10:31.320 --> 01:10:33.640
Did I get so lucky for 25 years?

01:10:33.640 --> 01:10:34.480
Nothing bad happened,

01:10:34.480 --> 01:10:35.880
nothing but bad things are gonna be happening.

01:10:35.880 --> 01:10:36.840
Am I cursed?

01:10:36.840 --> 01:10:38.680
Is my family cursed, right?

01:10:38.680 --> 01:10:40.760
And I think that leads to, you say,

01:10:40.760 --> 01:10:44.640
what the learning about the human mind, in retrospect,

01:10:44.640 --> 01:10:47.860
I think I understood at the time to some degree,

01:10:47.860 --> 01:10:50.600
but not like I do now, I can put words to it now, right?

01:10:50.600 --> 01:10:55.600
Like, how incredibly important, powerful,

