01:35:03.840 --> 01:35:07.040
You know, I love his writing and,

01:35:08.040 --> 01:35:12.040
you know, I think there was a streak of nihilism

01:35:12.040 --> 01:35:15.400
that I think grew in his writing over the years

01:35:15.400 --> 01:35:18.320
and the thought is, I think that Camus died by suicide.

01:35:18.320 --> 01:35:21.560
I think we're not sure of that because it was a car accident.

01:35:21.560 --> 01:35:25.400
But I've always read that as the primary scholarly opinion.

01:35:25.400 --> 01:35:27.960
And I think it's interesting that after his death,

01:35:27.960 --> 01:35:30.760
a book called The First Man was published,

01:35:30.760 --> 01:35:32.760
which I don't know if he had intended to publish.

01:35:32.760 --> 01:35:34.280
I don't remember the specifics about it,

01:35:34.280 --> 01:35:36.560
but it's about him as a child, right?

01:35:36.560 --> 01:35:38.000
And it's interesting, The First Man,

01:35:38.000 --> 01:35:41.320
even he was the first man in his existence, right?

01:35:41.320 --> 01:35:44.240
The most, you know, the one that felt and experienced

01:35:44.240 --> 01:35:47.640
everything and there's sadness and distress

01:35:47.640 --> 01:35:50.840
and all in that book, but there's a beauty of life

01:35:50.840 --> 01:35:52.320
and living and experience.

01:35:52.320 --> 01:35:56.800
And I think to compare that beauty, like that's life,

01:35:56.800 --> 01:35:58.880
even if something's difficult and scary and sad,

01:35:58.880 --> 01:36:00.480
like there's something beautiful around the corner

01:36:00.480 --> 01:36:02.840
and he's a kind person in the new discovery.

01:36:02.840 --> 01:36:05.240
You know, more what was in him as a child.

01:36:05.280 --> 01:36:07.960
And I think that we can get jaded as we get.

01:36:07.960 --> 01:36:09.520
As you and I were just talking about a few minutes ago,

01:36:09.520 --> 01:36:12.200
we can accentuate the negative and foster the negative

01:36:12.200 --> 01:36:15.960
and come to a place where we're looking for

01:36:15.960 --> 01:36:18.520
some in-depth philosophical answer, you know,

01:36:18.520 --> 01:36:21.360
some thick book, you know, that's gonna explain all that

01:36:21.360 --> 01:36:23.920
to us instead of the simplicity

01:36:23.920 --> 01:36:25.640
that we've been talking about.

01:36:25.640 --> 01:36:30.640
I think humility, gratitude helps us have just simple,

01:36:31.280 --> 01:36:33.480
positive experiences, feelings of contentment,

01:36:33.480 --> 01:36:35.320
feelings of connection with another person,

01:36:35.320 --> 01:36:36.680
learning, discovery.

01:36:36.680 --> 01:36:39.280
And I think the answer to Keimu's question is yes.

01:36:39.280 --> 01:36:43.320
And I think it lies in his writing about when he was a child,

01:36:43.320 --> 01:36:45.960
which I think he saw as less important

01:36:45.960 --> 01:36:48.800
than his later writings and the intellectual heaviness

01:36:48.800 --> 01:36:52.360
when I think maybe he had lost his way a little bit

01:36:52.360 --> 01:36:54.880
from the things he understood when he was younger.

01:36:54.880 --> 01:36:56.880
So another way to talk about it,

01:36:56.880 --> 01:36:59.760
and I'd love to hear what you think is

01:36:59.760 --> 01:37:02.480
about these broad categories.

01:37:03.320 --> 01:37:05.360
Let me be started with Kierkegaard

01:37:05.360 --> 01:37:09.000
of existentialism, absurdism, and nihilism.

01:37:09.000 --> 01:37:12.200
And I think Keimu considered himself an absurdist,

01:37:12.200 --> 01:37:13.800
not actually an existentialist.

01:37:13.800 --> 01:37:16.880
It's kind of a middle ground where I think existentialist,

01:37:19.320 --> 01:37:21.120
I don't wanna characterize it in the wrong way

01:37:21.120 --> 01:37:22.520
and there's a lot of different definitions,

01:37:22.520 --> 01:37:27.160
but I think existentialists ultimately do think

01:37:27.160 --> 01:37:31.320
that there is meaning in sort of pursuing

01:37:31.320 --> 01:37:33.360
the passion of life, like pursuing the mode,

01:37:33.360 --> 01:37:37.240
like in living life, that's where you discover the meaning

01:37:37.240 --> 01:37:41.680
at that individual level of fully embracing life.

01:37:42.920 --> 01:37:47.080
And I think sort of nihilism is again,

01:37:47.080 --> 01:37:48.080
it's kind of like a spectrum,

01:37:48.080 --> 01:37:52.040
but nihilism basically says there's no meaning

01:37:53.160 --> 01:37:56.600
and it doesn't matter, nothing matters.

01:37:57.560 --> 01:38:00.920
I don't even know, but somehow that lands you in a place

01:38:00.920 --> 01:38:02.920
that's totally uninspired.

01:38:02.920 --> 01:38:05.560
Maybe nihilists would disagree with that.

01:38:05.560 --> 01:38:08.320
Maybe there's a way to live a creative life

01:38:08.320 --> 01:38:10.280
in a nihilistic mindset.

01:38:10.280 --> 01:38:14.560
And I think absurdism is somewhere in the middle

01:38:14.560 --> 01:38:19.560
where pursuing meaning at all is not a good idea.

01:38:22.400 --> 01:38:23.960
So kind of, I think existentialists say

01:38:23.960 --> 01:38:25.600
you should be looking for meaning

01:38:25.600 --> 01:38:28.120
and it's to be discovered in your own actions,

01:38:28.120 --> 01:38:30.200
in your own life in the moment.

01:38:30.200 --> 01:38:34.480
And absurdism says life is absurd, nothing makes sense.

01:38:34.480 --> 01:38:37.640
Don't look for the meaning, just live, just be.

01:38:37.640 --> 01:38:42.640
I think that's kind of the later Camus kind of philosophy.

01:38:43.080 --> 01:38:44.360
I don't know if you can sort of comment

01:38:44.360 --> 01:38:47.400
on these kind of nuanced ideas here

01:38:47.400 --> 01:38:52.400
if there is no religious guide to your life.

01:38:54.240 --> 01:38:56.860
What do you think about this kind of search for meaning?

01:38:56.860 --> 01:38:58.520
Do you see that there's some wisdom

01:38:58.520 --> 01:39:01.680
in the existentialist perspective of discovering it

01:39:01.680 --> 01:39:03.760
in your own life and this passion

01:39:03.760 --> 01:39:06.280
and this kind of day-to-day existence

01:39:06.280 --> 01:39:08.200
in the moments of your life that bring you joy,

01:39:08.200 --> 01:39:09.040
that kind of thing.

01:39:09.040 --> 01:39:10.800
Bringing different sort of perspectives

01:39:10.800 --> 01:39:12.240
and trying to tease apart like, well, wait,

01:39:12.240 --> 01:39:14.520
what are the differences in those perspectives?

01:39:14.520 --> 01:39:17.120
And I think what it points out is that,

01:39:17.120 --> 01:39:19.800
okay, we tend to conflate things as human beings

01:39:19.800 --> 01:39:21.160
and to take two different things

01:39:21.160 --> 01:39:22.760
and try and make them into one.

01:39:22.760 --> 01:39:24.880
But we also, I think on the other end of the spectrum

01:39:24.880 --> 01:39:27.040
get very overly reductionist.

01:39:27.040 --> 01:39:30.400
And I think that when we get to overly reductionist,

01:39:30.400 --> 01:39:32.440
we lose the ability to learn from anything

01:39:32.440 --> 01:39:33.480
or to generate meaning, right?

01:39:33.480 --> 01:39:35.080
I mean, the thing about Sartre,

01:39:35.080 --> 01:39:37.200
who is the thought of existentialism

01:39:37.200 --> 01:39:38.680
is so consistent with him, right?

01:39:38.680 --> 01:39:43.200
Who on the one hand, wrote about very clear terms,

01:39:43.200 --> 01:39:44.680
like this is what it is and this is what it isn't.

01:39:44.680 --> 01:39:46.040
And here's how you're gonna make your meaning

01:39:46.040 --> 01:39:48.840
in a very like academically proscribed way.

01:39:48.840 --> 01:39:52.400
But he also wrote short stories like The Wall, right?

01:39:52.400 --> 01:39:54.960
Where there's something totally absurd happens, right?

01:39:54.960 --> 01:39:56.440
As part of the story, right?

01:39:56.480 --> 01:39:58.800
So I think what ends up happening

01:39:58.800 --> 01:40:00.320
is people either reduce themselves

01:40:00.320 --> 01:40:02.240
or get associated with something

01:40:02.240 --> 01:40:04.240
that by being overly reductionist

01:40:04.240 --> 01:40:06.000
takes us away from meaning, right?

01:40:06.000 --> 01:40:08.720
The idea that, look, we don't know

01:40:08.720 --> 01:40:12.320
if there is an overarching religious meaning

01:40:12.320 --> 01:40:14.720
or what we call a religious meaning or purpose.

01:40:14.720 --> 01:40:16.920
Like we don't know that, right?

01:40:16.920 --> 01:40:18.800
So, okay, if we take that as a given

01:40:18.800 --> 01:40:21.560
that people who say that they know are having faith,

01:40:21.560 --> 01:40:23.160
like Al Spinoza described faith, right?

01:40:23.160 --> 01:40:27.200
Faith is that you don't know, but you believe anyway, right?

01:40:27.200 --> 01:40:30.840
It's not because you have faith now you know something, right?

01:40:30.840 --> 01:40:32.920
Because I think that's a slippery slope

01:40:32.920 --> 01:40:35.280
to the persecution of others, right?

01:40:35.280 --> 01:40:38.600
So if we say, okay, we don't know,

01:40:38.600 --> 01:40:41.440
then, you know, we're left either deciding,

01:40:41.440 --> 01:40:43.760
okay, well then the hell with everything, you know?

01:40:43.760 --> 01:40:46.320
Like there's that movie, a strange brew, right?

01:40:46.320 --> 01:40:47.920
That Bob and Doug McKenzie were like,

01:40:47.920 --> 01:40:49.600
the brakes don't work on the car.

01:40:49.600 --> 01:40:52.160
And one of them says, oh, why bother steering, right?

01:40:52.160 --> 01:40:53.680
So if we don't know that there's meaning,

01:40:53.680 --> 01:40:54.520
like why bother steering?

01:40:54.520 --> 01:40:56.000
Let's just give up the ghost, right?

01:40:56.000 --> 01:40:58.240
And I don't think that's even what the nihilist said.

01:40:58.240 --> 01:40:59.880
I mean, I think the Coonan said,

01:40:59.880 --> 01:41:02.800
we should get rid of everything that we've ever created

01:41:02.800 --> 01:41:04.600
except Beethoven's Ninth Symphony

01:41:04.600 --> 01:41:06.240
and start over from there.

01:41:06.240 --> 01:41:08.360
But so even people who are very nihilistic

01:41:08.360 --> 01:41:10.120
or associated with that,

01:41:10.120 --> 01:41:12.600
a lot of them were just not liking what we had built, right?

01:41:12.600 --> 01:41:15.760
So if we accept that a lot of what we have built

01:41:15.760 --> 01:41:17.800
as humans inside of us and outside of us

01:41:17.800 --> 01:41:20.080
is really counterproductive and doesn't help us.

01:41:20.120 --> 01:41:23.160
And that absurd things happen in the world, right?

01:41:23.160 --> 01:41:26.200
And that often the way social structures and systems build up,

01:41:26.200 --> 01:41:28.080
you build themselves up is absurd.

01:41:28.080 --> 01:41:30.160
I think our healthcare system operates

01:41:30.160 --> 01:41:32.160
in a way that's absurd, right?

01:41:32.160 --> 01:41:34.560
So if we accept that there are absurdities

01:41:34.560 --> 01:41:36.640
that we don't know if there's truth,

01:41:36.640 --> 01:41:37.840
then what are we left with?

01:41:37.840 --> 01:41:40.840
But like, well, let's try and make meaning, right?

01:41:40.840 --> 01:41:42.760
Or Tega Igasset said,

01:41:42.760 --> 01:41:44.840
yoso yo e mi circunstancia, right?

01:41:44.840 --> 01:41:46.920
I'm myself in my circumstances, right?

01:41:46.920 --> 01:41:49.240
He was like, look, we can't control everything.

01:41:49.240 --> 01:41:52.000
We live in circumstances around us,

01:41:52.000 --> 01:41:54.120
but within those circumstances,

01:41:54.120 --> 01:41:58.080
we can make decisions and define ourselves.

01:41:58.080 --> 01:41:59.760
And I think the brilliance of that,

01:41:59.760 --> 01:42:01.920
and I think tying it all together, right?

01:42:01.920 --> 01:42:04.160
In a way that's not trying to be,

01:42:04.160 --> 01:42:05.360
in a sense it ties it all together

01:42:05.360 --> 01:42:08.280
by not trying to answer everything concisely,

01:42:08.280 --> 01:42:09.960
that yes, we can make meaning.

01:42:09.960 --> 01:42:12.600
Like we see that if someone trips in front of me,

01:42:12.600 --> 01:42:14.440
I could walk around them or I could help them up.

01:42:14.440 --> 01:42:17.840
I mean, no one can tell me that it doesn't matter what I do.

01:42:17.960 --> 01:42:19.960
I absolutely reject the idea that,

01:42:19.960 --> 01:42:22.280
oh, I could step over them or on them,

01:42:22.280 --> 01:42:24.120
or I could help them up and it doesn't matter.

01:42:24.120 --> 01:42:27.360
Oh yeah, try being the person on the ground, right?

01:42:27.360 --> 01:42:31.600
So we create meaning, but we live in our circumstances

01:42:31.600 --> 01:42:34.200
and there are absurdities both within us

01:42:34.200 --> 01:42:36.480
and outside of us in our social structures.

01:42:36.480 --> 01:42:37.400
And there are a lot of things

01:42:37.400 --> 01:42:40.080
that pretend to have meaning that don't.

01:42:40.080 --> 01:42:42.120
And there's the shades of nihilism,

01:42:42.120 --> 01:42:44.360
but ultimately there's something going on here

01:42:44.360 --> 01:42:45.640
that's doing the best we can

01:42:45.680 --> 01:42:47.440
in the context of just not knowing.

01:42:48.600 --> 01:42:50.600
Yeah, I tend to see, I don't know if it's genetic,

01:42:50.600 --> 01:42:53.880
I tend to think just observing the internet,

01:42:53.880 --> 01:42:55.400
the number of memes there are.

01:42:56.920 --> 01:42:58.960
I think many other people are like me.

01:42:58.960 --> 01:43:02.000
I tend to see the humor in the absurdity.

01:43:02.000 --> 01:43:04.000
I tend to enjoy it from that kind of angle.

01:43:04.000 --> 01:43:06.400
I see the Kafkaesque nature of society,

01:43:06.400 --> 01:43:07.960
different aspects of society,

01:43:07.960 --> 01:43:11.400
and just kind of notice the magic with a smile.

01:43:12.400 --> 01:43:15.880
And just laugh at the circus of it all.

01:43:15.880 --> 01:43:19.000
Cause it is magical that the circus all comes together.

01:43:19.000 --> 01:43:20.160
It's like a little bit out of sync

01:43:20.160 --> 01:43:22.440
and then just a guy playing trombone,

01:43:22.440 --> 01:43:24.360
but like overall it's pretty good.

01:43:24.360 --> 01:43:25.400
It's pretty good.

01:43:25.400 --> 01:43:28.400
And we can look at that and just kind of marvel go, huh.

01:43:28.400 --> 01:43:32.560
Which I think is a relation to at least a lot of what we

01:43:32.560 --> 01:43:34.680
in the Western world think of as Eastern,

01:43:34.680 --> 01:43:36.400
is like as non-attachment, right?

01:43:36.400 --> 01:43:38.640
Because then if there's something absurd,

01:43:38.640 --> 01:43:41.320
and it's like not good for me,

01:43:41.320 --> 01:43:42.640
then I accept that too,

01:43:42.640 --> 01:43:44.000
instead of getting angry about it,

01:43:44.000 --> 01:43:44.840
and railing about it,

01:43:44.840 --> 01:43:47.160
or seeing some cosmic meaning in it, right?

01:43:47.160 --> 01:43:49.120
I think there's also a healthy non-attachment

01:43:49.120 --> 01:43:50.640
in what you're saying too.

01:43:50.640 --> 01:43:53.440
So there's a, I mean, you mentioned Eastern thought.

01:43:53.440 --> 01:43:55.760
There's, just to ask in each year,

01:43:55.760 --> 01:44:00.480
but also Buddha have kind of spoke of life as suffering.

01:44:00.480 --> 01:44:02.020
Do you think there's truth to that?

01:44:02.020 --> 01:44:06.120
That suffering is a fundamental part of life.

01:44:06.120 --> 01:44:08.680
I think it is a fundamental part of life.

01:44:08.680 --> 01:44:11.840
I don't think that means that life is suffering, right?

01:44:11.840 --> 01:44:14.800
If we say, well, life is suffering, then what am I doing?

01:44:14.800 --> 01:44:16.760
That I'm trying to erase from my mind

01:44:16.760 --> 01:44:18.480
like the birth of my children, right?

01:44:18.480 --> 01:44:20.760
Things that were filled with joy, right?

01:44:20.760 --> 01:44:23.520
Like life is not entirely suffering,

01:44:23.520 --> 01:44:26.080
but life brings a lot of suffering.

01:44:26.080 --> 01:44:27.000
And for some people,

01:44:27.000 --> 01:44:29.720
it brings such disproportionate suffering

01:44:29.720 --> 01:44:31.520
and the people don't survive the suffering.

01:44:31.520 --> 01:44:34.680
And I think when people are conscientious and empathic,

01:44:34.680 --> 01:44:36.800
that really bothers us, right?

01:44:36.800 --> 01:44:38.080
The suffering in our own lives

01:44:38.080 --> 01:44:40.240
and the fact that others at times could,

01:44:40.240 --> 01:44:42.480
could it seem to be so overwhelmed by suffering

01:44:42.480 --> 01:44:45.120
that they don't even get a chance to see good.

01:44:45.120 --> 01:44:46.600
And I think that there's,

01:44:46.600 --> 01:44:48.120
I do think there's truth to that

01:44:48.120 --> 01:44:50.360
and there's sadness and distress to that,

01:44:50.360 --> 01:44:52.960
but to say therefore life is suffering,

01:44:52.960 --> 01:44:54.880
I think is completely untrue.

01:44:54.880 --> 01:44:57.000
And, you know, it ignores the fact

01:44:57.000 --> 01:44:58.600
that someone even made a trombone, right?

01:44:58.600 --> 01:45:00.240
Let alone that there's a little bit out of sync

01:45:00.240 --> 01:45:02.520
and someone's playing the trombone, like that's cool.

01:45:02.520 --> 01:45:05.400
There's, you know, there's elements of the absurd

01:45:05.400 --> 01:45:07.040
that you said are neat and interesting.

01:45:07.040 --> 01:45:10.680
And if we start accepting that we can't understand

01:45:10.680 --> 01:45:12.120
or control everything,

01:45:12.120 --> 01:45:15.200
then we can accept and I think really love

01:45:15.200 --> 01:45:18.520
and foster the beauty in our lives.

01:45:18.520 --> 01:45:21.560
Yeah, I think the word suffering

01:45:21.560 --> 01:45:24.120
is doing a little bit too much work.

01:45:24.120 --> 01:45:25.320
Because I think it's probably referring

01:45:25.320 --> 01:45:28.000
to the philosophical concept of that,

01:45:29.160 --> 01:45:31.880
yeah, there's the absurd, the absurdity.

01:45:31.880 --> 01:45:32.720
Right.

01:45:32.720 --> 01:45:34.880
That stuff just happens randomly.

01:45:34.880 --> 01:45:37.920
Evil people succeed, good people fail.

01:45:37.920 --> 01:45:41.560
There's a seeming random injustice on occasion.

01:45:41.560 --> 01:45:42.400
Right.

01:45:42.400 --> 01:45:44.680
And on occasion there's justice in,

01:45:45.720 --> 01:45:48.280
yeah, all of it that feels like,

01:45:49.400 --> 01:45:52.960
and maybe because often there's a lot of loss

01:45:52.960 --> 01:45:57.960
and then there's a kind of matching complimentary aspect

01:45:59.200 --> 01:46:02.640
to any good feeling that all comes crashing down,

01:46:02.640 --> 01:46:04.200
like every hello.

01:46:05.000 --> 01:46:08.080
From a physics perspective, ends in a goodbye.

01:46:13.200 --> 01:46:14.800
That's a really sad thing,

01:46:14.800 --> 01:46:19.800
like of all the amazing people I get to meet in my life,

01:46:20.280 --> 01:46:23.560
all the amazing experiences eventually they have to end.

01:46:23.560 --> 01:46:26.200
And that's part of what makes them amazing.

01:46:26.200 --> 01:46:27.840
But why is that sad?

01:46:27.840 --> 01:46:30.360
Is it because we're taught to think that it's like,

01:46:30.360 --> 01:46:32.360
look, at some point you and I are gonna say goodbye today.

01:46:32.360 --> 01:46:33.840
Like I hope we're richer for it.

01:46:33.880 --> 01:46:35.760
And then we take that goodness off with us.

01:46:35.760 --> 01:46:38.200
Like I wanna celebrate that

01:46:38.200 --> 01:46:39.880
because it's all part of the goodness.

01:46:39.880 --> 01:46:41.680
I think we're taught to think, oh, that's so bad.

01:46:41.680 --> 01:46:43.720
And it equates to death and misery.

01:46:43.720 --> 01:46:47.480
And I think it's often not that way.

01:46:47.480 --> 01:46:48.680
I think there is a sadness too,

01:46:48.680 --> 01:46:53.440
but I also don't think that sadness is a negative thing.

01:46:53.440 --> 01:46:56.320
It's a different way to celebrate a beautiful thing.

01:46:56.320 --> 01:46:58.320
So there's a melancholic nature to it,

01:46:58.320 --> 01:47:01.200
there's something passing of it leaving.

01:47:01.200 --> 01:47:03.640
I think it's that old Louis C.K. thing

01:47:03.640 --> 01:47:07.080
that I go back to over and over from his show, Louis,

01:47:07.080 --> 01:47:11.200
where he was all heartbroken,

01:47:11.200 --> 01:47:16.200
that he just broke up with somebody he loved.

01:47:16.480 --> 01:47:19.000
And he told about that to an old man.

