Then therapists are rationed, right?

02:14:58.920 --> 02:15:02.120
I mean, how many insurance panels have lists

02:15:02.120 --> 02:15:04.720
a mile long of qualified therapists

02:15:04.720 --> 02:15:07.680
who could be on that insurance panel,

02:15:07.680 --> 02:15:09.520
but there's a certification process.

02:15:09.520 --> 02:15:10.600
Like these is making no sense, right?

02:15:10.600 --> 02:15:12.760
The state's already certified the person, right?

02:15:12.760 --> 02:15:14.440
But there's so many barriers to entry

02:15:14.440 --> 02:15:16.920
that now we're rationing this resource,

02:15:16.920 --> 02:15:19.080
which we should all stop and pause for a second

02:15:19.080 --> 02:15:21.400
and think like we're okay with that as a society.

02:15:21.400 --> 02:15:23.360
And by the way, everything else is like that too,

02:15:23.360 --> 02:15:25.520
when we're trying to get help for our health.

02:15:25.520 --> 02:15:27.880
So let's step back from that for a second.

02:15:27.880 --> 02:15:30.920
Now it's a resource that's not in great supply.

02:15:30.920 --> 02:15:33.400
And then a person begins to think, you know,

02:15:33.400 --> 02:15:34.840
essentially I'll take what I can get.

02:15:34.840 --> 02:15:35.760
Like I just gotta get somebody

02:15:35.760 --> 02:15:37.960
and I don't know enough to know anyway, right?

02:15:37.960 --> 02:15:40.600
And those are very disempowering thoughts

02:15:40.600 --> 02:15:42.040
as opposed to saying, look,

02:15:42.040 --> 02:15:43.680
I'm gonna be an empowered consumer

02:15:43.680 --> 02:15:47.560
and I'm gonna need to choose someone who gets over

02:15:47.560 --> 02:15:48.960
just some basic hurdles

02:15:48.960 --> 02:15:52.040
of what I think are reasonable human interaction, right?

02:15:52.040 --> 02:15:53.720
So like as a person making eye contact,

02:15:53.720 --> 02:15:55.120
do they seem interested, right?

02:15:55.120 --> 02:15:57.640
Like these are basic points about any human interaction,

02:15:57.640 --> 02:15:59.440
including a therapist, right?

02:15:59.440 --> 02:16:01.200
Then you can say, okay, is there a word of mouth?

02:16:01.200 --> 02:16:02.360
Anyone else who has something good?

02:16:02.360 --> 02:16:04.240
Nothing better than a word of mouth recommendation

02:16:04.240 --> 02:16:06.000
from someone you trust, right?

02:16:06.000 --> 02:16:07.880
Or anybody can have a good website,

02:16:07.880 --> 02:16:09.200
but you say, let me look at the website.

02:16:09.200 --> 02:16:11.200
What is it saying if there is one, right?

02:16:11.880 --> 02:16:15.520
Does it resonate with me or not, right?

02:16:15.520 --> 02:16:16.840
But after all of that,

02:16:16.840 --> 02:16:19.040
then you go to see the person

02:16:19.040 --> 02:16:21.760
with the idea that you're interviewing them, right?

02:16:21.760 --> 02:16:24.000
The idea that, yeah, I hope this person can help me

02:16:24.000 --> 02:16:25.840
and if so, great, I'm with the program,

02:16:25.840 --> 02:16:27.160
but I'm thinking about it.

02:16:27.160 --> 02:16:28.680
Do I want this person?

02:16:28.680 --> 02:16:29.800
Do I feel heard?

02:16:29.800 --> 02:16:31.560
Do I feel cared for?

02:16:31.560 --> 02:16:33.440
Which doesn't mean, is it easy, right?

02:16:33.440 --> 02:16:34.680
It might mean, is it hard?

02:16:34.680 --> 02:16:38.720
And I leave and I feel like emotional for a couple of days

02:16:38.720 --> 02:16:41.720
but I see that I'm facing new things.

02:16:41.720 --> 02:16:43.800
No, this process of assessment

02:16:43.800 --> 02:16:46.840
so that one isn't settling for something

02:16:46.840 --> 02:16:48.960
that is formulaic over-packaged

02:16:48.960 --> 02:16:51.240
and I'm not trying to be overly critical of therapists.

02:16:51.240 --> 02:16:53.160
I mean, there are people everywhere who do their jobs well

02:16:53.160 --> 02:16:55.280
and people who don't do their jobs well,

02:16:55.280 --> 02:16:58.680
but most therapists are working in systems

02:16:58.680 --> 02:17:01.800
that push against doing the job well, right?

02:17:01.800 --> 02:17:03.040
Because they're rationing care

02:17:03.040 --> 02:17:04.600
and there's a lot of number of sessions

02:17:04.600 --> 02:17:07.120
and there's enough in such time before a person can return.

02:17:07.640 --> 02:17:09.200
So often it's an uphill battle

02:17:09.200 --> 02:17:10.960
because we're trying to be helped

02:17:10.960 --> 02:17:14.320
within systems we've created and tolerate

02:17:14.320 --> 02:17:17.640
that are pushing against helping us.

02:17:19.040 --> 02:17:23.040
Yeah, but that interview process is tricky.

02:17:23.040 --> 02:17:25.400
I mean, if you're in a rough place mentally,

02:17:27.160 --> 02:17:29.280
just like with any kind of interview,

02:17:29.280 --> 02:17:33.000
it's hard not to think that a failed interaction,

02:17:33.000 --> 02:17:37.440
failed interview, there's something wrong with you.

02:17:37.440 --> 02:17:38.800
Sure, right.

02:17:38.800 --> 02:17:41.000
There is an authority to a therapist, I think,

02:17:41.000 --> 02:17:44.720
where you think like they've got it all figured out.

02:17:44.720 --> 02:17:49.400
And I'm a mess and therefore if there's something off,

02:17:49.400 --> 02:17:51.680
it's all my fault, right?

02:17:51.680 --> 02:17:54.360
So it's a very tricky and then it's easy to then give up

02:17:54.360 --> 02:17:56.480
and then, because it's like that step

02:17:56.480 --> 02:18:00.160
to try to get a therapist, the first step to get help,

02:18:00.160 --> 02:18:01.920
if I get a therapist, like any kind of help,

02:18:01.960 --> 02:18:04.080
that's a big leap to take.

02:18:04.080 --> 02:18:05.720
Especially when you're in a rough place.

02:18:05.720 --> 02:18:06.920
I agree completely.

02:18:06.920 --> 02:18:11.560
We should not make people swim against such a strong current

02:18:11.560 --> 02:18:12.920
to get their needs met.

02:18:12.920 --> 02:18:15.240
I mean, we see this in such obvious places

02:18:15.240 --> 02:18:18.320
where you have an elderly, homebound person

02:18:18.320 --> 02:18:20.160
who can't get their medicine

02:18:20.160 --> 02:18:21.520
because oh, there's been some change

02:18:21.520 --> 02:18:24.200
and they didn't put the new number into the form

02:18:24.200 --> 02:18:25.040
or Lord knows what.

02:18:25.040 --> 02:18:28.760
I mean, it's incredible how we force people

02:18:28.760 --> 02:18:30.840
to swim against strong currents

02:18:30.880 --> 02:18:33.040
to get things that are just basic

02:18:33.040 --> 02:18:35.000
at times for their survival.

02:18:35.000 --> 02:18:38.320
And with that in mind, I don't have a lot of respect

02:18:38.320 --> 02:18:42.000
for where healthcare is at or where mental health is at.

02:18:42.000 --> 02:18:46.000
The field that I work in has accepted all sorts of aspects

02:18:47.520 --> 02:18:50.400
of how things go, someone else controlling

02:18:50.400 --> 02:18:53.560
how long the interaction can go on,

02:18:53.560 --> 02:18:55.080
how the interaction is bounded,

02:18:55.080 --> 02:18:56.160
what can be said and done,

02:18:56.160 --> 02:18:58.160
what medicines can be prescribed.

02:18:58.160 --> 02:19:00.840
There's so many external controls

02:19:00.840 --> 02:19:04.000
in the systems we work in that we,

02:19:04.000 --> 02:19:07.920
and I say me included, like all of us in the field

02:19:07.920 --> 02:19:09.840
have let it get to a place

02:19:09.840 --> 02:19:13.280
where it's obscenely difficult to get help.

02:19:13.280 --> 02:19:15.040
Obscenely difficult.

02:19:15.040 --> 02:19:18.920
And we should say that's not okay.

02:19:18.920 --> 02:19:21.840
I think psychiatrists and therapists

02:19:21.840 --> 02:19:24.760
and masters level social workers, psychologists

02:19:24.760 --> 02:19:27.440
and you name it, I think we should all say

02:19:27.560 --> 02:19:29.520
this is not okay.

02:19:29.520 --> 02:19:31.400
And then we as a society should be saying

02:19:31.400 --> 02:19:33.320
this is not okay, otherwise what you're saying

02:19:33.320 --> 02:19:35.440
which is I think completely true

02:19:35.440 --> 02:19:38.680
will only become worse as there's more and more barriers

02:19:38.680 --> 02:19:40.120
to getting the help a person needs.

02:19:40.120 --> 02:19:42.280
And each time a person isn't helped,

02:19:42.280 --> 02:19:44.640
it sets the odds against them getting more help.

02:19:44.640 --> 02:19:47.760
I should say here that when I started working

02:19:47.760 --> 02:19:49.360
there were times I would send people

02:19:49.360 --> 02:19:50.360
to an emergency room, right?

02:19:50.360 --> 02:19:52.960
If there was some emergency in their mental health

02:19:52.960 --> 02:19:54.240
and they were at risk.

02:19:54.240 --> 02:19:55.680
And there were times I'd send somebody

02:19:55.680 --> 02:19:58.240
to an emergency room where if you stopped and looked

02:19:58.240 --> 02:20:01.400
it would have been malpractice not to do that, right?

02:20:01.400 --> 02:20:06.400
Now it's not just me who has an incredibly high threshold

02:20:08.480 --> 02:20:09.960
for sending someone to an emergency room

02:20:09.960 --> 02:20:12.600
because you just send someone who's in a lot of distress

02:20:12.600 --> 02:20:15.480
and oftentimes they're sitting on a gurney in a hallway

02:20:15.480 --> 02:20:17.520
or they're locked in a small white room

02:20:17.520 --> 02:20:19.280
and all they had was depression.

02:20:19.280 --> 02:20:22.280
They're scared when they go in and 36 hours later,

02:20:22.280 --> 02:20:23.400
oh, they're feeling a little better.

02:20:23.400 --> 02:20:24.920
Wags are desperate to get out of there.

02:20:25.040 --> 02:20:26.280
And someone sends them home.

02:20:26.280 --> 02:20:29.840
I mean, so our systems have shifted so much

02:20:29.840 --> 02:20:33.200
that we tolerate now en masse.

02:20:33.200 --> 02:20:35.360
What is egregious to the individual?

02:20:37.320 --> 02:20:42.320
So you are a psychiatrist in terms of doing therapy,

02:20:42.760 --> 02:20:46.240
psychotherapy, what does the successful interaction

02:20:46.240 --> 02:20:47.240
look like?

