It's like, we're two humans,

02:24:27.680 --> 02:24:29.160
but if you're doing something for me,

02:24:29.160 --> 02:24:31.400
then there's something you have an expertise and I don't.

02:24:31.400 --> 02:24:32.840
That's why you're doing it for me.

02:24:32.840 --> 02:24:35.120
The reverse could be true, but it doesn't mean we're not.

02:24:35.120 --> 02:24:37.720
Just two humans doing something together.

02:24:37.720 --> 02:24:39.840
And the healthcare system and the legal system

02:24:39.840 --> 02:24:40.920
should not get in the way of that.

02:24:40.920 --> 02:24:43.520
I mean, there's liability and all these kinds of things

02:24:43.520 --> 02:24:48.440
that can get in the way of the humanness.

02:24:49.360 --> 02:24:50.760
I mean, some of that is justified.

02:24:50.760 --> 02:24:51.640
You have to be careful.

02:24:51.640 --> 02:24:54.720
You have to make sure there's a force for irresponsible,

02:24:54.720 --> 02:24:57.960
but a little too much can destroy the humanness.

02:24:57.960 --> 02:24:58.840
I'll use it where I don't.

02:24:58.840 --> 02:25:00.840
You usually say something is insane.

02:25:00.840 --> 02:25:02.720
Like it's not consistent with sanity.

02:25:02.720 --> 02:25:07.480
And the presence of the legal system, look, I'm all four.

02:25:07.480 --> 02:25:09.360
Of course, physicians have to be held,

02:25:09.360 --> 02:25:12.120
but to be responsible and everybody makes mistakes

02:25:12.120 --> 02:25:15.120
and people have to be accountable for their mistakes,

02:25:15.120 --> 02:25:17.320
I understand all of that.

02:25:17.320 --> 02:25:21.760
But what we see now, it's so absurd that,

02:25:21.760 --> 02:25:24.720
oh, like everyone is frightened, right?

02:25:24.720 --> 02:25:25.800
Everyone is frightened.

02:25:25.800 --> 02:25:26.920
And then just looking to like,

02:25:26.920 --> 02:25:28.280
how do I slot into the box,

02:25:28.280 --> 02:25:31.040
check the boxes of what I'm supposed to do

02:25:31.040 --> 02:25:32.880
and not get in trouble?

02:25:32.880 --> 02:25:37.000
People get sued because someone was at that hospital

02:25:37.000 --> 02:25:38.640
and that doctor touched their care.

02:25:38.640 --> 02:25:39.800
This happens in the VA system.

02:25:39.800 --> 02:25:41.560
It happens in other systems too.

02:25:41.560 --> 02:25:42.880
So you might have touched their care

02:25:42.880 --> 02:25:44.560
and no one's even saying you did anything wrong,

02:25:44.560 --> 02:25:46.000
but they say the next person did.

02:25:46.000 --> 02:25:47.680
Oh, someone settled on your behalf

02:25:47.680 --> 02:25:49.360
and now you have a malpractice.

02:25:49.360 --> 02:25:51.880
Dang, and maybe you can't get a license somewhere else.

02:25:51.880 --> 02:25:56.000
Like doctors are terrified and they're terrified for good,

02:25:56.000 --> 02:25:57.320
they're terrified for good reason

02:25:57.320 --> 02:26:00.080
because the same society that has given doctors

02:26:00.080 --> 02:26:02.000
in many ways too much power over time

02:26:02.000 --> 02:26:05.400
and treated doctors maybe too much like gods now

02:26:05.440 --> 02:26:09.000
is I think enacting some of society's anger and envy

02:26:09.000 --> 02:26:10.680
out on the physicians.

02:26:10.680 --> 02:26:13.840
Even the idea that like a person would know what medicine,

02:26:13.840 --> 02:26:16.520
like I saw a couple of TV commercials give me this.

02:26:16.520 --> 02:26:18.680
It's like, it's interesting, right?

02:26:18.680 --> 02:26:21.640
Because even if, let's say I take myself out of it,

02:26:21.640 --> 02:26:22.680
it doesn't feel good obviously,

02:26:22.680 --> 02:26:24.600
but it takes about, it's like, wow,

02:26:24.600 --> 02:26:26.640
like I went to school for like eight years for this

02:26:26.640 --> 02:26:28.600
and you don't even want to hear my opinion, right?

02:26:28.600 --> 02:26:30.480
You're not taking good care of yourself, right?

02:26:30.480 --> 02:26:32.520
It doesn't mean you should think my opinion is gospel

02:26:32.520 --> 02:26:36.280
as I said it, but people then don't have an understanding

02:26:36.280 --> 02:26:37.640
of like, what is expertise?

02:26:37.640 --> 02:26:39.120
What do people learn?

02:26:39.120 --> 02:26:42.760
How can people help us understand and make better decisions?

02:26:42.760 --> 02:26:44.480
It kind of goes out with the wash

02:26:44.480 --> 02:26:47.520
and then the position of the expert.

02:26:47.520 --> 02:26:48.920
I mean, a lot has been written about this, right?

02:26:48.920 --> 02:26:52.840
It gets diminished over time very much to our own peril.

02:26:52.840 --> 02:26:56.080
And then often with aggression in the medical world

02:26:56.080 --> 02:26:59.880
coming back towards the alleged expert.

02:26:59.880 --> 02:27:03.920
Yeah, expertise is a tricky one, such a tricky thing

02:27:03.920 --> 02:27:08.920
because couple with expertise,

02:27:10.720 --> 02:27:13.000
the attention is this arrogance

02:27:13.000 --> 02:27:14.920
that can come with expertise.

02:27:14.920 --> 02:27:18.040
The arrogance can make the expert feel

02:27:18.040 --> 02:27:22.080
like they're more of an expert and there's a vicious cycle

02:27:22.080 --> 02:27:25.080
and then the arrogance in the current in the 21st century,

02:27:25.080 --> 02:27:26.000
especially with the internet,

02:27:26.000 --> 02:27:29.680
the arrogance can completely force the public

02:27:29.680 --> 02:27:30.960
to distrust the expert

02:27:30.960 --> 02:27:34.000
because all they see is the arrogance versus the expertise.

02:27:34.000 --> 02:27:36.960
So ultimately you have to have,

02:27:36.960 --> 02:27:41.160
I think the greatest experts and masters I know

02:27:41.160 --> 02:27:44.360
are the ones that have complete humility.

02:27:44.360 --> 02:27:45.880
Right, humility and gratitude.

02:27:45.880 --> 02:27:46.720
And gratitude.

02:27:46.720 --> 02:27:47.560
Be this back.

02:27:47.560 --> 02:27:49.480
Which is usually a really good sign

02:27:49.480 --> 02:27:53.280
that somebody is at the top of their field.

02:27:53.280 --> 02:27:54.120
Right.

02:27:54.120 --> 02:27:55.640
And they'll acknowledge that they don't know everything.

02:27:55.640 --> 02:27:56.480
Right.

02:27:56.480 --> 02:27:57.400
Which is hilarious, right?

02:27:57.400 --> 02:28:01.520
So like the best experts I know are the ones

02:28:01.520 --> 02:28:05.640
that will say that they don't know.

02:28:05.640 --> 02:28:06.480
Right.

02:28:06.480 --> 02:28:08.160
They would not call themselves an expert.

02:28:08.160 --> 02:28:09.000
Right.

02:28:09.000 --> 02:28:09.840
Right.

02:28:09.840 --> 02:28:10.680
It's very confusing.

02:28:10.680 --> 02:28:11.520
Right.

02:28:11.520 --> 02:28:12.360
Or know that they know a lot

02:28:12.360 --> 02:28:13.480
but don't know the answer to this.

02:28:13.480 --> 02:28:14.640
You see that a lot in medicine.

02:28:14.640 --> 02:28:16.680
That person knows they're an expert surgeon

02:28:16.680 --> 02:28:18.520
but they also acknowledge they don't know

02:28:18.520 --> 02:28:20.280
if this is the right time to operate.

02:28:20.280 --> 02:28:21.760
That's how you get to the best answer

02:28:21.760 --> 02:28:23.240
instead of someone who is an expert

02:28:23.240 --> 02:28:24.560
and always knows the answer.

02:28:24.560 --> 02:28:25.680
Yeah.

02:28:25.680 --> 02:28:28.200
If we actually rewind to the beginning

02:28:28.200 --> 02:28:29.920
of our conversation, we talked about,

02:28:30.880 --> 02:28:33.400
you mentioned something I wanted to return to.

02:28:33.400 --> 02:28:36.560
So there's layers that are,

02:28:36.560 --> 02:28:38.760
there's an emergent novelty.

02:28:38.760 --> 02:28:40.720
And you mentioned that we as human beings

02:28:40.720 --> 02:28:43.960
and we introspect on our own mind,

02:28:43.960 --> 02:28:46.220
we really can't know most of it.

02:28:47.200 --> 02:28:50.160
Which of course makes me think of this,

02:28:50.160 --> 02:28:52.520
the unconscious mind, the subconscious mind

02:28:52.520 --> 02:28:53.520
and Carl Jung.

02:28:53.520 --> 02:28:55.560
How much is hiding there in the shadows?

02:28:55.560 --> 02:28:58.960
You've investigated a lot of trauma.

02:28:58.960 --> 02:29:00.880
How much is there in our mind

02:29:00.880 --> 02:29:03.520
that's not directly accessible to us?

02:29:03.520 --> 02:29:06.520
Like what can you say maybe philosophically

02:29:06.520 --> 02:29:11.520
about how much is there lurking in the Jungian shadow?

02:29:13.440 --> 02:29:15.880
I think there's a tremendous amount there.

02:29:15.880 --> 02:29:19.640
But I wouldn't, I don't immediately go to

02:29:20.560 --> 02:29:21.960
an ominous perspective, right?

02:29:21.960 --> 02:29:23.440
Because if it's lurking there, right,

02:29:23.440 --> 02:29:24.720
it can come get us, right?

02:29:24.720 --> 02:29:26.760
And to some extent, that's true, right?

02:29:26.760 --> 02:29:28.320
Because the seeds of evil are there

02:29:28.320 --> 02:29:30.000
if we want to plant and nurture them.

02:29:30.000 --> 02:29:32.200
You think good things can't lurk?

02:29:32.200 --> 02:29:34.880
I guess so, I was being poetic.

02:29:34.880 --> 02:29:35.960
But you're right, you're absolutely right.

02:29:35.960 --> 02:29:38.160
And the Jungian shadow is supposed to not just be

02:29:38.160 --> 02:29:39.840
dark things, it's supposed to be everything.

02:29:39.840 --> 02:29:42.100
It's supposed to be a lot of positive things as well, yeah.

02:29:42.100 --> 02:29:46.080
Right, which I think brings us to self-knowledge to truth

02:29:46.080 --> 02:29:49.320
where I think the opposite of envy,

02:29:49.320 --> 02:29:53.560
narcissism, sociopathy, I do think is all rooted in truth.

02:29:53.560 --> 02:29:55.960
It's both the truth of the good things about us

02:29:55.960 --> 02:29:58.760
or the ways we're not, we're not blameable

02:29:58.760 --> 02:30:00.960
for the, blame worthy for the things we're blaming ourselves

02:30:00.960 --> 02:30:02.240
for, et cetera.

02:30:02.240 --> 02:30:04.760
But the self-knowledge and the truth

02:30:04.760 --> 02:30:09.100
and getting away from the reflex of anger, frustration,

02:30:09.100 --> 02:30:13.280
envy, shame, what I think happens then is all of that

02:30:13.280 --> 02:30:14.320
underneath the surface.

02:30:14.320 --> 02:30:16.160
If we look at like the consciousness is the top

02:30:16.160 --> 02:30:18.240
of the iceberg, you know, outside the top.

02:30:18.240 --> 02:30:19.720
So well, outside the water.

02:30:19.720 --> 02:30:22.320
So is what's underneath like shifting

02:30:22.320 --> 02:30:24.200
and it can pull the top under, right?

02:30:24.200 --> 02:30:26.080
Or is it supporting the top?

02:30:26.080 --> 02:30:30.240
And really, I believe is honesty, truth,

02:30:30.240 --> 02:30:32.120
self-knowledge, humility, gratitude,

02:30:32.120 --> 02:30:34.760
all this simple stuff, good mental health

02:30:34.760 --> 02:30:36.600
is always consistent with simplicity.

02:30:36.600 --> 02:30:39.600
You know, humility, gratitude or easy things to say.

02:30:39.600 --> 02:30:41.280
Like we know what that is, right?

02:30:41.280 --> 02:30:42.680
We understand what that is.

02:30:42.680 --> 02:30:46.400
Soothing envy by having immense power

02:30:46.400 --> 02:30:49.040
and subjugating others is getting very, very complicated,

02:30:49.040 --> 02:30:51.560
right, what that is and how that plays out.

02:30:51.560 --> 02:30:54.200
So if we are in touch with ourselves,

02:30:54.200 --> 02:30:57.280
if we're honest with ourselves, if we own what's ours,

02:30:57.280 --> 02:30:59.680
we don't try and own what's not ours, right?

02:30:59.680 --> 02:31:02.360
What happens then is something isn't waiting inside of us

02:31:02.360 --> 02:31:06.760
to sort of jump us with some new fact of self

02:31:06.760 --> 02:31:08.400
or challenge of self, right?

02:31:08.400 --> 02:31:10.800
Then I think what happens are phenomena

02:31:10.800 --> 02:31:13.480
like intrinsic learning, like the way that so much happens

02:31:13.480 --> 02:31:15.560
inside of us automatically, right?

02:31:15.560 --> 02:31:18.880
How people who have high levels of expertise

02:31:18.880 --> 02:31:23.800
know the answer to complex questions more rapidly, right?

02:31:23.800 --> 02:31:25.760
It doesn't take them longer to think through it,

02:31:25.760 --> 02:31:27.480
but they have more knowledge to think through.

02:31:27.480 --> 02:31:30.600
It's that more happens rapidly and unconsciously

02:31:30.600 --> 02:31:33.360
so they know the more complex answer

02:31:33.360 --> 02:31:35.240
more quickly and readily, right?

02:31:35.240 --> 02:31:37.080
And we can build that in ourselves,

02:31:37.080 --> 02:31:39.480
not just in terms of factual knowledge,

02:31:39.480 --> 02:31:42.280
but in terms of how we respond to things, right?

02:31:42.280 --> 02:31:46.040
If I make a mistake, do I respond with reflexive shame, right?

02:31:46.040 --> 02:31:47.640
If I see someone has something I'd like,

02:31:47.640 --> 02:31:49.160
how do I respond?

02:31:49.160 --> 02:31:51.800
We're more in accord with ourselves

02:31:51.800 --> 02:31:56.480
and then the automaticity in us is serving us better.

02:31:56.480 --> 02:31:57.520
So that's in the positive.

02:31:57.520 --> 02:31:59.360
Do you think, do you draw some wisdom

02:31:59.360 --> 02:32:03.800
from the early pioneers of psychotherapy

02:32:03.800 --> 02:32:05.840
like Freud and Jung?

02:32:05.840 --> 02:32:06.680
Yes.

02:32:06.680 --> 02:32:07.680
That there's some repressed,

02:32:09.920 --> 02:32:12.440
there's some stuff to work through

02:32:12.440 --> 02:32:15.760
that is in the unconscious mind.

02:32:15.760 --> 02:32:20.400
Yes, I think there's always like 100% of the time.

02:32:20.400 --> 02:32:21.440
If you have a living human,

02:32:21.440 --> 02:32:24.680
you have things to work through in the unconscious mind, right?

02:32:24.680 --> 02:32:26.560
There's too much that goes on around us

02:32:26.560 --> 02:32:30.200
that we might find unacceptable and suppressed, right?

02:32:30.200 --> 02:32:33.800
There can be smaller but important examples, right?

02:32:33.800 --> 02:32:38.520
Someone who feels that they're not a good enough parent

02:32:38.520 --> 02:32:43.520
and they, I don't know, they dropped the child's plate, right?

02:32:43.760 --> 02:32:48.760
And there's a feeling about that of badness in them

02:32:50.160 --> 02:32:53.520
that the person that can't tolerate and pushes away, right?

02:32:53.520 --> 02:32:55.520
And maybe they become a little bit less confident,

02:32:55.520 --> 02:32:56.640
a little bit less assertive.

02:32:56.640 --> 02:32:59.720
Like those small examples are important

02:32:59.720 --> 02:33:01.240
because they may be low valence,

02:33:01.240 --> 02:33:04.240
but there can be many, many, many, many, many of them, right?

02:33:04.240 --> 02:33:06.240
Then you can look at the opposite end of the spectrum

02:33:06.240 --> 02:33:09.880
where someone, for example, feels or they're repressing

02:33:09.880 --> 02:33:12.440
their sexuality unconsciously.

02:33:12.440 --> 02:33:15.480
Something that is so important, say,

02:33:15.480 --> 02:33:16.920
to how a person feels about themselves,

02:33:16.920 --> 02:33:18.400
to whether they can seek fulfillment,

02:33:18.400 --> 02:33:20.840
to how they feel about their ability to interact

02:33:20.840 --> 02:33:23.040
and engage with others in ways that are loving

02:33:23.040 --> 02:33:24.800
and generative over time.

02:33:24.800 --> 02:33:28.000
So from smaller things that accumulate

02:33:28.000 --> 02:33:30.880
often at a rapid pace to really big things,

02:33:30.880 --> 02:33:33.200
we are pushing things into the unconscious

02:33:33.200 --> 02:33:36.520
because they're not acceptable and we need to explore.

02:33:36.520 --> 02:33:38.000
Like why is that not acceptable?

02:33:38.000 --> 02:33:39.440
Maybe there's a non-acceptable urge

02:33:39.440 --> 02:33:41.440
because it's really not acceptable to me, right?

02:33:41.440 --> 02:33:42.720
Like a violent urge.

02:33:42.720 --> 02:33:44.760
Maybe there's an unacceptable urge

02:33:44.760 --> 02:33:47.720
because I'm actually listening to the lie society

02:33:47.720 --> 02:33:50.520
is telling me about what's okay and what's not okay, right?

02:33:50.520 --> 02:33:52.680
So in exploring those things,

02:33:52.680 --> 02:33:54.960
yes, we become happier and healthier

02:33:54.960 --> 02:33:58.000
and that could mean if we're already happy and healthy,

02:33:58.000 --> 02:34:01.240
it gets better, we get more insulated against the negative

02:34:01.240 --> 02:34:03.680
or it can mean the person who's really nurturing

02:34:03.680 --> 02:34:07.360
some of those seeds of evil and envy does that less

02:34:07.360 --> 02:34:08.840
or steps away from it.

02:34:08.840 --> 02:34:10.440
So whether it's good or it's bad,

02:34:10.440 --> 02:34:13.760
it's in there inside of us and we benefit

02:34:13.760 --> 02:34:16.880
from understanding that idea of the observing ego, right?

02:34:16.880 --> 02:34:18.680
Like I said, the part that can stop and say,

02:34:18.680 --> 02:34:22.240
hey, this is what's, I see what's going on in me.

02:34:22.240 --> 02:34:25.360
What have you learned about exploring the human mind

02:34:25.360 --> 02:34:27.480
about the art of conversation?

02:34:27.480 --> 02:34:29.560
Is ultimately therapy is conversation.

02:34:29.560 --> 02:34:30.600
Yeah.

02:34:30.600 --> 02:34:33.280
Is there something you can put into words?

02:34:33.280 --> 02:34:34.120
Yeah.

02:34:34.120 --> 02:34:37.400
Like what makes a good conversation?

02:34:37.400 --> 02:34:41.680
I think language is among the most amazing gifts we have.

02:34:41.680 --> 02:34:45.360
And it's also one of the most like clunky routes

02:34:45.360 --> 02:34:47.040
to misunderstanding, right?

02:34:47.040 --> 02:34:49.120
I think of like, there's a concept of facticity,

02:34:49.120 --> 02:34:50.600
you know, things that are like, I guess,

02:34:50.600 --> 02:34:52.960
a necessary evils and from the religious perspective,

02:34:52.960 --> 02:34:54.520
I think is where the word started,

02:34:54.520 --> 02:34:57.400
but of language being like a facticity, right?

02:34:57.400 --> 02:34:59.560
That we need to communicate with one another,

02:34:59.560 --> 02:35:01.600
we want to communicate so we develop words

02:35:01.600 --> 02:35:03.720
and we have these amazing brains that can have language

02:35:03.720 --> 02:35:05.640
and that's all well and good,

02:35:05.640 --> 02:35:08.600
but our fantasy would be more like Mr. Spock, right?

02:35:08.600 --> 02:35:10.000
You know, the Vulcan mind meld.

02:35:10.000 --> 02:35:11.520
It was like, I communicate with you

02:35:11.520 --> 02:35:12.840
because we put our hands on one another

02:35:12.840 --> 02:35:15.040
and we know, you know, by doing this,

02:35:15.040 --> 02:35:17.340
what we're thinking and what we're feeling

02:35:17.340 --> 02:35:19.540
and we won't have misunderstanding.

02:35:19.540 --> 02:35:22.480
So because I think we can approximate that,

02:35:22.480 --> 02:35:25.360
we can come kind of close with language, right?

02:35:25.360 --> 02:35:28.120
Or we can be so far away from it

02:35:28.120 --> 02:35:31.280
that we can say the same word and have opposite meanings

02:35:31.280 --> 02:35:34.000
and have it generate immediate animosity, right?

02:35:34.000 --> 02:35:37.360
That we need to be very, very careful

02:35:37.360 --> 02:35:40.320
with language, with communication, with conversations.

02:35:40.320 --> 02:35:43.280
And I've come to understand that much, much more

02:35:43.280 --> 02:35:46.480
as I've gotten older, both in terms of how hurtful,

02:35:47.840 --> 02:35:49.880
you know, reckless speeches,

02:35:49.880 --> 02:35:52.440
which is why I'm horrified by so much of what we see

02:35:52.440 --> 02:35:53.920
in our political discourse, right?

02:35:53.920 --> 02:35:57.240
The slurs, the negativity that's attached to something,

02:35:57.240 --> 02:36:00.200
to some word, you know, how one can utter something

02:36:00.200 --> 02:36:02.920
and it can go into another person just into the ear,

02:36:02.920 --> 02:36:05.040
but then goes through so many parts of the meaning

02:36:05.040 --> 02:36:07.400
of the brain that that person feels a pervasive sense

02:36:07.400 --> 02:36:10.440
of shame or beleagueredness, right?

02:36:10.440 --> 02:36:15.000
So yes, reckless language absolutely hurts people

02:36:15.000 --> 02:36:16.820
and we see that all the time in ways

02:36:16.820 --> 02:36:18.560
that I think are just atrocious.

02:36:18.560 --> 02:36:22.520
And also how bad miscommunication harms us.

02:36:22.520 --> 02:36:24.440
I mean, I really learned that through a lot

02:36:24.440 --> 02:36:26.480
of different ways, but in the work as a therapist

02:36:26.480 --> 02:36:28.520
of like really wanting to make sure

02:36:28.520 --> 02:36:30.560
that I'm really understanding you

02:36:30.560 --> 02:36:32.480
and you're really understanding me.

02:36:32.480 --> 02:36:34.840
And a lot of work goes into that communication.

02:36:34.840 --> 02:36:36.440
I think people, we can get into a rhythm of it

02:36:36.440 --> 02:36:38.120
and then it happens more easily,

02:36:38.120 --> 02:36:41.560
but I think it's like, it's a life and death difference

02:36:41.560 --> 02:36:44.120
at times, you know, lots of times, right?

02:36:44.120 --> 02:36:46.080
In the world around us between clear

02:36:46.080 --> 02:36:47.280
and accurate communication.

02:36:47.280 --> 02:36:48.440
And just so I said a word because like,

02:36:48.440 --> 02:36:51.000
I think you know what I mean or something like that.

02:36:51.000 --> 02:36:54.640
Yeah, so to that, I mean, there's the Camus quote

02:36:54.640 --> 02:36:58.320
that I like as much unhappiness as coming to the world

02:36:58.320 --> 02:37:00.320
because of things left unsaid.

02:37:01.080 --> 02:37:05.120
So that has to do with clear communication.

02:37:06.560 --> 02:37:11.560
But there's also a dance to a conversation,

02:37:12.680 --> 02:37:17.680
a poetry to it, there is ambiguity to language.

02:37:17.760 --> 02:37:20.640
And if you have a kind of awareness of that ambiguity

02:37:20.640 --> 02:37:23.520
and you play with it, that's where wit and humor come in.

02:37:23.520 --> 02:37:27.680
That allows you to sneak up to difficult topics

02:37:27.680 --> 02:37:30.480
without sort of trampling on them.

02:37:30.480 --> 02:37:34.200
I don't know, there's an art to it as well.

02:37:34.200 --> 02:37:36.520
There's an art to the silence, you know?

02:37:37.520 --> 02:37:40.320
Just allowing both human beings,

02:37:40.320 --> 02:37:41.920
one of the most intimate things you can share

02:37:41.920 --> 02:37:43.480
with a human being is silence.

02:37:43.480 --> 02:37:45.040
Yeah, that's communication.

02:37:45.040 --> 02:37:46.800
It's a different communication,

02:37:46.800 --> 02:37:48.880
but it ties in more powerful.

02:37:48.880 --> 02:37:53.320
Yeah, giving a person space to accumulate,

02:37:53.320 --> 02:37:56.040
to integrate, to make sense of their thoughts,

02:37:56.040 --> 02:37:58.840
enough to say a word, maybe a memory is sparked

02:37:58.840 --> 02:38:00.960
so they can think about that memory

02:38:00.960 --> 02:38:03.240
and process that memory.

02:38:03.240 --> 02:38:04.560
So it's not just words, sorry to do quick,

02:38:04.560 --> 02:38:05.480
it's not just words, right?

02:38:05.480 --> 02:38:06.760
Because now you're talking about communication

02:38:06.760 --> 02:38:11.080
as it's body language, it's expressions of empathy,

02:38:11.080 --> 02:38:13.440
it's movements, it's pauses, right?

02:38:13.440 --> 02:38:17.240
The communication process is very, very complicated

02:38:17.240 --> 02:38:18.720
and deep.

02:38:18.720 --> 02:38:20.800
Yeah, and some of that is building trust

02:38:20.800 --> 02:38:22.960
but also challenging a person.

02:38:22.960 --> 02:38:24.600
I wonder about that whole process

02:38:25.040 --> 02:38:26.600
with strangers, for example,

02:38:28.080 --> 02:38:29.560
of how you do that successfully.

02:38:29.560 --> 02:38:31.680
Like you and I just met today.

02:38:32.880 --> 02:38:37.280
But I think a lot of our interaction is very free.

02:38:37.280 --> 02:38:39.800
We can get to know each other in any way we want.

02:38:39.800 --> 02:38:42.920
There's a few conversations I have coming up

02:38:42.920 --> 02:38:44.920
in general where there's a lot of other pressures

02:38:44.920 --> 02:38:46.680
and constraints on those conversations.

02:38:46.680 --> 02:38:49.800
There's a danger to it, there's risks.

02:38:49.800 --> 02:38:51.560
There's the political forces involved,

02:38:51.560 --> 02:38:54.360
like not from my perspective,

02:38:54.360 --> 02:38:58.200
but probably from my as well of how do you say this thing?

02:38:58.200 --> 02:39:00.560
What are the words that are going to offend?

02:39:00.560 --> 02:39:02.840
And you're learning that about a stranger

02:39:02.840 --> 02:39:04.920
at the same time, and you don't.

02:39:06.760 --> 02:39:10.880
It's an interesting dance because you have to walk

02:39:10.880 --> 02:39:12.760
carefully but deliberately, right?

02:39:12.760 --> 02:39:17.200
Carefully because I've learned this about myself,

02:39:17.200 --> 02:39:18.400
about others.

02:39:18.400 --> 02:39:21.560
There's certain words that can trigger a person

02:39:22.440 --> 02:39:25.600
that can make a person feel poorly,

02:39:25.600 --> 02:39:28.160
like shitty about themselves.

02:39:29.600 --> 02:39:32.040
So you can push, you can challenge a person

02:39:32.040 --> 02:39:34.800
about something and they're totally okay with it,

02:39:34.800 --> 02:39:36.880
but if you use a certain word to do it,

02:39:36.880 --> 02:39:40.280
it's gonna, it's maybe it maps it to some childhood thing

02:39:40.280 --> 02:39:43.080
that their father or mother used to say or something like this.

02:39:43.080 --> 02:39:46.360
And I mean, part of the art of conversation

02:39:46.360 --> 02:39:49.160
is actually being a little bit free

02:39:49.160 --> 02:39:52.000
and using those words, but being extremely sensitive

02:39:52.000 --> 02:39:55.560
in detecting when a person reacts to a particular word

02:39:55.560 --> 02:39:57.600
and like storing that away.

02:39:57.600 --> 02:40:01.560
It's like, okay, then we might wanna return to that later

02:40:01.560 --> 02:40:03.240
because there might be an interesting,

02:40:03.240 --> 02:40:04.480
that could be a tip of an iceberg

02:40:04.480 --> 02:40:06.640
that's actually representing something beautiful,

02:40:06.640 --> 02:40:09.800
or you might wanna just, it's a nothing word

02:40:09.800 --> 02:40:12.720
that you just wanna avoid because it's a distraction.

02:40:12.720 --> 02:40:15.120
And so all of that kind of has to be integrated

02:40:15.120 --> 02:40:17.600
into the dance of language, which is really interesting,

02:40:17.600 --> 02:40:19.120
especially when the stakes are really high.

02:40:19.120 --> 02:40:20.800
When you get one conversation,

02:40:20.800 --> 02:40:24.360
when you sit down, you have one conversation

02:40:24.360 --> 02:40:26.960
and it makes the difference between,

02:40:26.960 --> 02:40:29.240
like say you had one conversation with a patient,

02:40:29.240 --> 02:40:31.440
this is the only conversation you get to help them.

02:40:31.440 --> 02:40:32.640
Sometimes it is the case.

02:40:32.640 --> 02:40:35.680
Yeah, this is pretty high stakes.

02:40:35.680 --> 02:40:37.500
Yeah. Oh man.

02:40:38.880 --> 02:40:39.720
Yeah, it's tough.

02:40:39.720 --> 02:40:43.360
I guess you get over, and like over time,

02:40:43.360 --> 02:40:47.520
I guess you get used to the high stakes nature

02:40:48.360 --> 02:40:49.840
when you develop an ability

02:40:49.840 --> 02:40:52.680
and all that unconscious processing, right?

02:40:52.680 --> 02:40:54.160
All that part of the iceberg

02:40:54.160 --> 02:40:56.320
that's underneath the surface is doing all of that, right?

02:40:56.320 --> 02:40:59.360
It's reading, behavioral cues, verbal cues,

02:40:59.360 --> 02:41:03.800
and recognizing the primacy of emotion over logic, right?

02:41:03.800 --> 02:41:05.840
If we're all logic, it'd be different.

02:41:05.840 --> 02:41:06.920
Okay, we're gonna talk about this thing.

02:41:06.920 --> 02:41:08.420
I'll say things, you say things back,

02:41:08.420 --> 02:41:10.600
even if it's politically contentious, say.

02:41:10.600 --> 02:41:12.120
It's okay, we're just gonna talk logically,

02:41:12.120 --> 02:41:13.920
but that's not the case, right?

02:41:13.920 --> 02:41:17.420
There could be a word that raises a certain emotion

02:41:17.420 --> 02:41:18.860
and you don't wanna tread there

02:41:18.860 --> 02:41:20.340
because the emotion will color

02:41:20.340 --> 02:41:22.060
the person's ability to engage,

02:41:22.060 --> 02:41:24.660
and so you're aware of all of this.

02:41:24.660 --> 02:41:27.300
And then I think from the perspective of all of that,

02:41:27.300 --> 02:41:29.500
I mean, it's like standing on the shoulders

02:41:29.500 --> 02:41:31.660
of your own internal giant, right?

02:41:31.660 --> 02:41:35.020
That understands language and emotions

02:41:35.020 --> 02:41:38.300
and body language and attunement and history

02:41:38.300 --> 02:41:40.100
and triggering and all of that.

02:41:40.100 --> 02:41:41.900
And then on top of that,

02:41:41.900 --> 02:41:43.340
as you're standing up on those shoulders,

02:41:43.340 --> 02:41:45.540
you're trying to be effective, right?

02:41:45.540 --> 02:41:48.340
And then I think that's where effectiveness

02:41:48.340 --> 02:41:51.180
can be unilateral or it can be together.

02:41:51.180 --> 02:41:53.700
I mean, I think some of what emerged

02:41:53.700 --> 02:41:54.940
from Victor Frankl's writing

02:41:54.940 --> 02:41:58.300
after the Second World War was how much

02:41:58.300 --> 02:42:00.340
a shared humanness means to us,

02:42:00.340 --> 02:42:02.860
how much of that can be an incentive

02:42:02.860 --> 02:42:05.480
for survival beyond all others, right?

02:42:05.480 --> 02:42:07.980
So the idea of are we doing something

02:42:07.980 --> 02:42:09.580
if we're communicating unilateral,

02:42:09.580 --> 02:42:12.580
like I want information from you

02:42:12.580 --> 02:42:14.620
or I want you to do a certain thing

02:42:14.660 --> 02:42:16.860
when we're done talking, right?

02:42:16.860 --> 02:42:17.940
Done communicating.

02:42:17.940 --> 02:42:20.820
That's a very unilateral type of effectiveness

02:42:20.820 --> 02:42:21.860
which can make sense.

02:42:21.860 --> 02:42:23.500
Sometimes I want information out of a patient

02:42:23.500 --> 02:42:25.100
because I want to know what to do next, right?

02:42:25.100 --> 02:42:26.980
So it doesn't have to always be negative

02:42:26.980 --> 02:42:29.420
but it can also be a tool of manipulation, right?

02:42:29.420 --> 02:42:31.900
If someone would say coming from envy or narcissism,

02:42:31.900 --> 02:42:33.460
I want to communicate with you

02:42:33.460 --> 02:42:36.060
in a way that makes you do what I want you to do, right?

02:42:36.060 --> 02:42:39.620
Different from that is where it's a shared communication

02:42:39.620 --> 02:42:42.780
where there's like an umbrella, so to speak over us

02:42:42.780 --> 02:42:46.100
and we're doing something that can only happen together

02:42:46.100 --> 02:42:48.420
because we're us, we're each person, right?

02:42:48.420 --> 02:42:50.380
And we come together to do something

02:42:50.380 --> 02:42:51.900
that's a shared effectiveness.

02:42:51.900 --> 02:42:54.540
Like I think we're doing now of like elucidating

02:42:54.540 --> 02:42:57.420
and pursuing thoughts and getting ideas out.

02:42:57.420 --> 02:42:59.180
And I think the best situations

02:42:59.180 --> 02:43:01.260
are shared effectiveness situations

02:43:01.260 --> 02:43:03.220
because you call upon the resourcefulness

02:43:03.220 --> 02:43:05.980
and the internal resources of both people.

02:43:05.980 --> 02:43:09.340
But you, especially with strangers,

02:43:09.340 --> 02:43:12.100
especially when it's not labeled a therapy session,

02:43:13.420 --> 02:43:18.420
you kind of actually stumble into that cooperative state.

02:43:18.740 --> 02:43:23.740
Like you have to organically develop a trust together

02:43:28.180 --> 02:43:30.420
and almost lose yourself.

02:43:30.420 --> 02:43:32.420
Ultimately, I do, I think you put it really nice.

02:43:32.420 --> 02:43:34.100
I think successful conversations,

02:43:34.100 --> 02:43:38.980
even when it's with like, even if it's like with world leaders

02:43:38.980 --> 02:43:42.740
or logicians, people that operate in the space of reason,

02:43:42.740 --> 02:43:46.260
the most successful conversation will ultimately be

02:43:46.260 --> 02:43:49.980
in the layer and the landscape of emotion.

02:43:49.980 --> 02:43:52.260
Like that's where the interesting stuff will happen.

02:43:52.260 --> 02:43:53.780
That's where you discover anything.

02:43:53.780 --> 02:43:55.540
And that's where you get to actually meet,

02:43:55.540 --> 02:43:58.060
to start getting an understanding of each other.

02:43:58.060 --> 02:44:01.460
Or what you actually mean even by the statements

02:44:01.460 --> 02:44:04.260
that are supposed to be kind of rationally based.

02:44:05.460 --> 02:44:06.940
It's like you lose yourself.

02:44:06.940 --> 02:44:08.380
You lose yourself in the way you do

02:44:08.380 --> 02:44:12.180
when you're children and you're just not shooting the shit

02:44:12.180 --> 02:44:14.780
about whatever topic and you just forget yourself.

02:44:14.780 --> 02:44:15.620
Forget the things you're supposed to say.

02:44:15.620 --> 02:44:17.140
You lose yourself in the context, right?

02:44:17.140 --> 02:44:20.940
Yeah, where you kind of plug into the unconscious mind

02:44:20.940 --> 02:44:24.740
a little bit and you get to speak maybe indirectly,

02:44:24.740 --> 02:44:27.980
but to the things that really drive you,

02:44:27.980 --> 02:44:31.940
to the things, to the emotions, I suppose,

02:44:31.940 --> 02:44:35.180
that underlie your worldview.

02:44:35.180 --> 02:44:38.340
I feel like that's where productive conversations

02:44:38.900 --> 02:44:41.660
can happen, whether it's a patient or just a stranger

02:44:41.660 --> 02:44:45.220
you're talking to at a bar about geopolitics.

02:44:46.300 --> 02:44:47.740
You mentioned Victor Frankel.

02:44:47.740 --> 02:44:50.460
What do you make of his work, Man's Search for Meaning?

02:44:50.460 --> 02:44:53.540
What are the lessons you draw from his work?

02:44:53.540 --> 02:44:56.820
Of him as a psychologist, but also from that

02:44:56.820 --> 02:44:59.540
very powerful work that reflects on his experience

02:44:59.540 --> 02:45:02.060
in a Nazi concentration camp.

02:45:02.060 --> 02:45:03.020
Yeah.

02:45:03.020 --> 02:45:08.020
I think that it was almost a profound

02:45:08.780 --> 02:45:11.940
reinvention of humanness, right?

02:45:11.940 --> 02:45:16.940
After something so awful, so bleak and so despairing

02:45:17.740 --> 02:45:22.740
to speak anew about shared humanness, human connection,

02:45:25.660 --> 02:45:30.660
meaning, compassion, that I think it was an intellectual

02:45:31.980 --> 02:45:36.860
direction that was adorned with all of the emotions

02:45:36.900 --> 02:45:39.660
that we need to adorn the logic with

02:45:39.660 --> 02:45:42.340
in order to make real change in the world.

02:45:42.340 --> 02:45:47.340
And I think that his work has fueled so many branches

02:45:47.580 --> 02:45:51.740
have come from his work, the existential psychotherapy

02:45:51.740 --> 02:45:56.060
and its place in helping human activities today, right?

02:45:57.220 --> 02:46:02.220
A trend away from the idea that we're all quite isolated

02:46:02.660 --> 02:46:04.300
and that what's going on between us

02:46:04.300 --> 02:46:05.860
is all very transactional, right?

02:46:06.020 --> 02:46:07.300
Putting something out and you take it in,

02:46:07.300 --> 02:46:09.020
you put something out, I take it in, right?

02:46:09.020 --> 02:46:10.540
The idea that, no, there's a difference there.

02:46:10.540 --> 02:46:13.860
There's a shared humanness that creates a meaning

02:46:13.860 --> 02:46:15.340
beyond the transactional.

02:46:15.340 --> 02:46:16.340
Kind of like you were just saying,

02:46:16.340 --> 02:46:18.740
the logical stuff isn't really that interesting

02:46:18.740 --> 02:46:21.500
because the logic is there's an answer

02:46:21.500 --> 02:46:22.420
to whatever logic is.

02:46:22.420 --> 02:46:23.780
We can do math, right?

02:46:23.780 --> 02:46:27.380
It's where does the surprises come in, right?

02:46:27.380 --> 02:46:30.700
Either in terms of wonderful behavior

02:46:30.700 --> 02:46:32.220
or destructive behavior, right?

02:46:32.220 --> 02:46:34.020
They're coming from people's emotions.

02:46:34.060 --> 02:46:36.580
So that's what we want to understand.

02:46:36.580 --> 02:46:39.180
And that occurs in the context of a person

02:46:39.180 --> 02:46:40.380
and other humans, you know,

02:46:40.380 --> 02:46:42.180
even if it's the conception of someone

02:46:42.180 --> 02:46:44.900
and all and other humans as enemy, you know,

02:46:44.900 --> 02:46:49.220
or it's the conception of two people sitting together,

02:46:49.220 --> 02:46:51.060
the idea that there's a shared humanness

02:46:51.060 --> 02:46:52.900
and it's not all transactional

02:46:52.900 --> 02:46:57.900
and that he could take that out of the pinnacle

02:46:57.980 --> 02:47:01.380
of human tragedy and utilize it in a way

02:47:01.380 --> 02:47:05.820
that informs us being better as a species going forward,

02:47:05.820 --> 02:47:08.060
I think is really monumental.

02:47:08.060 --> 02:47:10.740
What do you think is the role of emotion

02:47:10.740 --> 02:47:15.060
in the human mind, in the human condition?

02:47:15.060 --> 02:47:18.140
Because you've, we've talked several times

02:47:18.140 --> 02:47:21.860
in different ways that emotion matters

02:47:21.860 --> 02:47:23.860
and it's a big part of who we are.

02:47:25.420 --> 02:47:28.340
But why is it there?

02:47:28.340 --> 02:47:29.620
Why is it useful?

02:47:29.620 --> 02:47:30.900
What's good about it?

02:47:31.740 --> 02:47:35.460
We've almost said it's almost like a negative thing

02:47:35.460 --> 02:47:37.380
that we just have to live with.

02:47:37.380 --> 02:47:39.660
But why is it also maybe a beautiful thing?

02:47:39.660 --> 02:47:40.500
Yeah.

02:47:40.500 --> 02:47:42.020
Well, I think you said, what's the role of emotion?

02:47:42.020 --> 02:47:43.340
I think emotion is the king

02:47:43.340 --> 02:47:44.500
if we want to use that analogy.

02:47:44.500 --> 02:47:47.060
It's the CEO if you want to use that analogy, right?

02:47:47.060 --> 02:47:49.940
Emotion rules all.

02:47:49.940 --> 02:47:51.740
We're taught that we're logical creatures,

02:47:51.740 --> 02:47:54.100
but we have innumerable pieces of data

02:47:54.100 --> 02:47:55.940
even over the course of just a day,

02:47:55.940 --> 02:47:57.780
let alone a human experience

02:47:57.780 --> 02:47:59.500
to tell us that is not the truth.

02:47:59.500 --> 02:48:02.500
Is it ever logical to run into a burning building?

02:48:03.380 --> 02:48:04.340
No, right?

02:48:04.340 --> 02:48:06.140
I mean, logic is never gonna tell one to do that.

02:48:06.140 --> 02:48:07.500
Okay, so many love is in the building.

02:48:07.500 --> 02:48:10.620
The person's already sprinted halfway to the building, right?

02:48:10.620 --> 02:48:15.420
Emotion rules us and so the thought,

02:48:15.420 --> 02:48:18.820
a thought is some of that is evolutionary, right?

02:48:18.820 --> 02:48:21.980
That strong negative emotion stays with us

02:48:21.980 --> 02:48:24.220
very, very profoundly, right?

02:48:24.220 --> 02:48:26.780
So example I'll give is if we're hunter-gatherers

02:48:26.780 --> 02:48:29.140
and like I find a new berry and it tastes good

02:48:29.140 --> 02:48:32.300
and it seems nutritious and then, and it is, right?

02:48:32.300 --> 02:48:34.780
Everything's fine, it'd be good to remember that, right?

02:48:34.780 --> 02:48:36.660
But if I find a new berry and it tastes good

02:48:36.660 --> 02:48:39.060
and it seems nutritious and we both eat it

02:48:39.060 --> 02:48:43.260
and almost die of sickness, we better remember that, right?

02:48:43.260 --> 02:48:48.260
So the primacy of emotion is in us for reasons

02:48:48.660 --> 02:48:49.900
that are about survival,

02:48:49.900 --> 02:48:52.460
that the emotion of it's my child in that building

02:48:52.460 --> 02:48:55.180
or my loved one is why I don't give a damn about logic

02:48:55.180 --> 02:48:56.860
and run into the building, right?

02:48:56.860 --> 02:48:58.900
The emotion of I thought that was good

02:48:58.900 --> 02:49:01.460
and I got really sick and I better never forget

02:49:01.460 --> 02:49:02.980
is also about survival.

02:49:02.980 --> 02:49:04.380
And the same applies to humans.

02:49:04.380 --> 02:49:06.660
If we're from different tribes back then

02:49:06.660 --> 02:49:09.260
and in my tribe, when you put your hand out,

02:49:09.260 --> 02:49:11.420
it's a greeting in your tribe,

02:49:11.420 --> 02:49:13.580
if someone puts their hand out, it means,

02:49:13.580 --> 02:49:16.100
