03:01:01.280 --> 03:01:03.000
and when there's a lot of conflict

03:01:03.000 --> 03:01:05.560
in between Northern Ireland and Ireland, right?

03:01:05.560 --> 03:01:06.960
And you thought, wow, there's not,

03:01:06.960 --> 03:01:08.560
there's not even a look difference, right?

03:01:08.560 --> 03:01:11.640
It's the same general religious umbrella,

03:01:11.640 --> 03:01:12.680
same ethnicity, right?

03:01:12.680 --> 03:01:14.560
But now there's some religious difference.

03:01:14.560 --> 03:01:17.160
And I thought, it's not me trying to be denigrating,

03:01:17.160 --> 03:01:18.640
you know, around the Irish conflicts,

03:01:18.640 --> 03:01:20.240
like that's human of,

03:01:20.240 --> 03:01:22.320
oh, there's no actual difference between us.

03:01:22.320 --> 03:01:23.920
If I don't feel good about myself,

03:01:23.920 --> 03:01:25.680
I'm gonna find one, right?

03:01:25.680 --> 03:01:30.240
It's that, that I believe could go away.

03:01:30.240 --> 03:01:32.320
It's driven by maybe the trauma

03:01:32.320 --> 03:01:33.600
of just being alive in the world

03:01:33.600 --> 03:01:34.800
and things can happen to us,

03:01:34.800 --> 03:01:38.720
but we certainly promote in the human created trauma,

03:01:38.720 --> 03:01:41.400
people feeling not good enough, finding differences.

03:01:41.400 --> 03:01:43.280
There's a place for the envy to attach

03:01:43.280 --> 03:01:46.520
and we're off to the races of, you know, wars.

03:01:46.520 --> 03:01:48.080
I mean, we're talking about the Second World War

03:01:48.080 --> 03:01:50.320
and we think, well, what have we learned since then?

03:01:50.320 --> 03:01:51.160
It would take us a day

03:01:51.160 --> 03:01:53.960
to map out all the wars since then, right?

03:01:53.960 --> 03:01:55.360
Let alone for goodness sakes,

03:01:55.360 --> 03:01:57.320
everything that's salient right now.

03:01:57.320 --> 03:01:59.840
So we're not pretty, we're not good at learning

03:01:59.840 --> 03:02:03.320
from what seemed to be some very salient lessons.

03:02:05.320 --> 03:02:08.440
I should mention one thing is that I also know

03:02:08.440 --> 03:02:11.680
that you're interested in Russian culture a little bit.

03:02:11.680 --> 03:02:12.520
Yes.

03:02:13.680 --> 03:02:15.840
Churchill said, I cannot forecast to you

03:02:15.840 --> 03:02:17.840
the action of Russia.

03:02:17.840 --> 03:02:20.680
It is a riddle wrapped in a mystery inside an enigma.

03:02:20.680 --> 03:02:23.840
So what do you or some interesting differences

03:02:24.320 --> 03:02:27.960
between, so this Eastern part of the world

03:02:27.960 --> 03:02:30.560
of Russia, Ukraine, the Slavic countries,

03:02:30.560 --> 03:02:32.720
the former Soviet Union, all of that

03:02:32.720 --> 03:02:35.080
versus sort of the U.S. culture?

03:02:35.080 --> 03:02:37.120
What stands out to you from the literature,

03:02:37.120 --> 03:02:40.960
from the music, from the science, all that kind of stuff?

03:02:40.960 --> 03:02:45.960
I think there's so much intensity and I guess

03:02:47.840 --> 03:02:51.600
I would say fearlessness of expression

03:02:51.640 --> 03:02:55.600
that I see in the Slavic culture.

03:02:55.600 --> 03:02:58.480
Maybe it's across cultures

03:02:58.480 --> 03:03:00.480
because there's a different way that expression occurs.

03:03:00.480 --> 03:03:03.080
We say like, oh, it's different in the French

03:03:03.080 --> 03:03:05.720
than the Spanish or it's different than in parts of Africa.

03:03:05.720 --> 03:03:08.360
And I think when you take that part of the world

03:03:08.360 --> 03:03:10.960
for whatever reason, and maybe it's just totally random

03:03:10.960 --> 03:03:13.480
or maybe it's aspects of geography

03:03:13.480 --> 03:03:17.040
and experience and migration, but there's such an intensity.

03:03:17.040 --> 03:03:21.440
And I remember listening to Tchaikovsky very early on,

03:03:22.280 --> 03:03:23.640
for the very first time, early on in my life,

03:03:23.640 --> 03:03:26.920
or reading Dostoevsky and feeling like,

03:03:26.920 --> 03:03:31.920
oh, Dostoevsky's willingness, his ability and his willingness

03:03:32.320 --> 03:03:37.120
to express and create such powerful,

03:03:37.120 --> 03:03:40.080
aberrant states of human experience.

03:03:40.080 --> 03:03:43.360
Tchaikovsky in his music, the depths of suffering

03:03:43.360 --> 03:03:47.120
that it expresses has always stood out to me

03:03:48.120 --> 03:03:52.040
as a way that like if that's like the brightest light,

03:03:52.040 --> 03:03:54.040
so to speak, communicating information,

03:03:54.040 --> 03:03:56.160
that that's a place to look.

03:03:56.160 --> 03:03:59.800
And it's also a place that resonated with me so strongly

03:03:59.800 --> 03:04:03.440
because I think for some people who are informative years

03:04:03.440 --> 03:04:05.800
and having very difficult feelings, right?

03:04:05.800 --> 03:04:07.880
Of like a depth of feeling of like fear

03:04:07.880 --> 03:04:09.520
and how's the world gonna be?

03:04:09.520 --> 03:04:10.600
Am I gonna be annihilated?

03:04:10.600 --> 03:04:11.920
Am I, what do I even want?

03:04:11.920 --> 03:04:15.080
What do I feel inside of me to encounter

03:04:15.120 --> 03:04:18.280
that being expressed so intensely?

03:04:18.280 --> 03:04:21.240
I found to be very, very moving.

03:04:21.240 --> 03:04:22.880
So I don't know if that's a good answer or not,

03:04:22.880 --> 03:04:24.960
but I think there's an intensity of expression

03:04:24.960 --> 03:04:26.240
and a fearlessness.

03:04:26.240 --> 03:04:28.840
Dostoevsky wrote about terrible things.

03:04:28.840 --> 03:04:31.000
What happens in the person?

03:04:31.000 --> 03:04:34.360
Is there a person who is brilliant intellectually

03:04:34.360 --> 03:04:39.240
and very persuasive and very capable of being effective

03:04:39.240 --> 03:04:42.880
who also just chooses to be a child rapist, right?

03:04:42.880 --> 03:04:44.360
I mean, he wrote about that.

03:04:44.480 --> 03:04:48.960
He wrote about the truths of this is what we can be as humans.

03:04:48.960 --> 03:04:52.440
And I think there's so many lessons, including the truth.

03:04:52.440 --> 03:04:53.400
Like people will tend to think,

03:04:53.400 --> 03:04:56.320
oh, evil is not very bright or not very intelligent.

03:04:56.320 --> 03:04:58.720
That's a way to let evil propagate, right?

03:04:58.720 --> 03:05:01.600
Evil can be effective and attractive

03:05:01.600 --> 03:05:05.480
and very compelling, but evil nonetheless.

03:05:05.480 --> 03:05:08.240
And I just think there's a fearless willingness

03:05:08.240 --> 03:05:10.200
to look at that and to describe it.

03:05:10.200 --> 03:05:14.200
That I see primarily I've studied in Russian culture.

03:05:14.200 --> 03:05:16.080
Yeah, the fearless exploration

03:05:16.080 --> 03:05:18.840
of this whole human drama.

03:05:18.840 --> 03:05:20.640
Definitely Dostoevsky and others since

03:05:20.640 --> 03:05:23.240
in the 20th century and the 19th century have done

03:05:23.240 --> 03:05:24.360
an incredible job of that.

03:05:24.360 --> 03:05:25.560
Some of that, just like you said,

03:05:25.560 --> 03:05:27.320
is the language, the culture.

03:05:27.320 --> 03:05:30.440
I think that intense romanticism is there.

03:05:30.440 --> 03:05:35.440
That is almost an overdramatic exploration of human nature.

03:05:37.920 --> 03:05:41.480
It can err on the side or falter

03:05:41.480 --> 03:05:45.680
when it goes into a kind of cynical view of life.

03:05:45.680 --> 03:05:47.400
Life is suffering.

03:05:47.400 --> 03:05:49.840
I think that also has to do with the way you deal

03:05:49.840 --> 03:05:52.840
with the trauma of the world wars and so on.

03:05:52.840 --> 03:05:54.480
This is something the different nations

03:05:54.480 --> 03:05:57.160
throughout Europe had to do with that in different ways.

03:05:57.160 --> 03:05:59.400
Some of them have channeled into envy and resentment.

03:05:59.400 --> 03:06:04.400
Some of them channeled into a kind of nihilism or cynicism.

03:06:05.360 --> 03:06:09.680
And ultimately the intensity of feeling is there,

03:06:09.720 --> 03:06:12.520
which is sort of interesting to see

03:06:12.520 --> 03:06:14.160
and interesting how that manifests itself

03:06:14.160 --> 03:06:19.000
in the kind of governments it builds up.

03:06:19.000 --> 03:06:24.000
There's more authoritarianism in that part of the world

03:06:24.840 --> 03:06:27.160
versus the Western world that's more focused

03:06:27.160 --> 03:06:29.240
on the individual versus the collective.

03:06:29.240 --> 03:06:31.160
And when more focused on the individual,

03:06:31.160 --> 03:06:34.240
you have a propensity to value individual rights

03:06:34.240 --> 03:06:35.720
with democracy and so on.

03:06:35.720 --> 03:06:37.280
It's interesting to watch and yeah,

03:06:37.280 --> 03:06:40.080
to reconstruct how that all came to be.

03:06:40.080 --> 03:06:42.880
Is it in the blood?

03:06:42.880 --> 03:06:44.520
Is it in the mind?

03:06:44.520 --> 03:06:48.000
Is it in some kind of thing that more ethereal,

03:06:48.000 --> 03:06:49.720
a collective set of ideas that we pass

03:06:49.720 --> 03:06:52.720
from generation to generation between each other,

03:06:52.720 --> 03:06:54.920
sort of the collective of it?

03:06:54.920 --> 03:06:57.680
Yeah, it's fascinating to see.

03:06:57.680 --> 03:07:00.640
But now reinvigorated because there's conflict

03:07:00.640 --> 03:07:01.840
in that part of the world.

03:07:02.880 --> 03:07:06.040
You've also thought about the Cold War.

03:07:06.160 --> 03:07:09.040
What lessons about the human mind

03:07:09.040 --> 03:07:10.800
about psychiatry, psychology,

03:07:11.840 --> 03:07:14.280
and about looking at the Cold War?

03:07:15.440 --> 03:07:18.120
Can we take forward in the 21st century

03:07:18.120 --> 03:07:21.520
so that we can avoid World War III?

03:07:21.520 --> 03:07:22.360
Right.

03:07:22.360 --> 03:07:26.800
A major cold or hot war in the 21st century?

03:07:26.800 --> 03:07:27.760
Yeah.

03:07:27.760 --> 03:07:30.920
Well, I think unspoken animosities are very,

03:07:30.920 --> 03:07:32.360
very, very dangerous.

03:07:32.360 --> 03:07:34.520
I mean, right, it was a Cold War.

03:07:34.520 --> 03:07:38.280
There was fighting through proxies, right?

03:07:38.280 --> 03:07:41.840
The superpowers were fighting surrogate wars

03:07:41.840 --> 03:07:43.480
through proxies, which of course,

03:07:43.480 --> 03:07:46.080
in and of itself causes immense suffering.

03:07:46.080 --> 03:07:51.080
But it becomes the opposite of an exchange of ideas

03:07:51.360 --> 03:07:53.040
or an exchange of thought.

03:07:53.040 --> 03:07:55.080
You know, I remember the Khrushchev, right?

03:07:55.080 --> 03:07:57.720
Not believing that the kitchen could look like it did

03:07:57.720 --> 03:07:59.000
at the World's Fair, right?

03:07:59.000 --> 03:08:02.080
And some of the misconceptions here

03:08:02.080 --> 03:08:04.480
of like what things were like in Russia, right?

03:08:05.480 --> 03:08:08.160
It was a thought that those other people

03:08:08.160 --> 03:08:09.680
are not actually people, right?

03:08:09.680 --> 03:08:12.400
There's an enemy society of evil,

03:08:12.400 --> 03:08:14.680
which then paints with a broad brush

03:08:14.680 --> 03:08:16.560
in a way that makes it easy,

03:08:16.560 --> 03:08:18.040
too easy for the Cold War,

03:08:18.040 --> 03:08:20.320
for it to go from being cold, right?

03:08:20.320 --> 03:08:23.680
To have it boiling over into utter destruction.

03:08:23.680 --> 03:08:27.240
And I wrote, it was really a true story

03:08:27.240 --> 03:08:31.520
that when I was in, it was still the Soviet Union,

03:08:31.520 --> 03:08:32.600
but it was right around the time

03:08:32.600 --> 03:08:34.360
the Soviet Union was coming to an end.

03:08:34.880 --> 03:08:39.880
And it had gone on a trip for students from England.

03:08:39.920 --> 03:08:42.480
And we got to go places that people like, I hadn't gone.

03:08:42.480 --> 03:08:45.720
You know, foreigners hadn't gone in many, many years.

03:08:45.720 --> 03:08:48.800
It was just kind of the right timing to experience that.

03:08:48.800 --> 03:08:52.760
And like it really is true that someone said on short notice

03:08:52.760 --> 03:08:56.480
to these poor kids that like these group of Americans

03:08:56.480 --> 03:08:58.480
were coming and I have a picture somewhere

03:08:58.480 --> 03:09:00.640
of the kid in a gas mask.

03:09:00.640 --> 03:09:03.520
Like as they went under their desks and put on a gas mask

03:09:03.520 --> 03:09:07.400
and they thought, right, that's what, I mean, that's what,

03:09:08.440 --> 03:09:09.640
they're taught to think about us

03:09:09.640 --> 03:09:11.520
and we're taught to think about them.

03:09:11.520 --> 03:09:15.600
And like now we're back in an us them, right?

03:09:15.600 --> 03:09:18.400
When, you know, we're all trying to survive

03:09:18.400 --> 03:09:23.400
and we're all such, you know, human life is so delicate,

03:09:24.520 --> 03:09:25.360
right?

03:09:25.360 --> 03:09:27.280
You know, let alone human happiness

03:09:27.280 --> 03:09:30.560
and we make these divisions and we create this aggression

03:09:30.560 --> 03:09:31.600
and latent aggression.

03:09:31.600 --> 03:09:33.240
I mean, during the Cold War, we developed, right,

03:09:33.240 --> 03:09:35.400
the ability to destroy the earth, right?

03:09:35.400 --> 03:09:37.720
And then just sat looking at one another, you know,

03:09:37.720 --> 03:09:40.360
with further growing misunderstanding

03:09:40.360 --> 03:09:42.760
and the opportunity for the proxy fights.

03:09:42.760 --> 03:09:44.880
Like I said, the Cuban Missile Crisis,

03:09:44.880 --> 03:09:47.240
which I know wasn't a war, but it's an aspect of that, right?

03:09:47.240 --> 03:09:50.640
Where we just have ourselves wildly, you know,

03:09:50.640 --> 03:09:54.680
at risk of destruction without any mutual understanding.

03:09:54.680 --> 03:09:57.640
And again, I would argue that that is the opposite

03:09:57.640 --> 03:09:59.480
of the counter entropy, right?

03:09:59.480 --> 03:10:01.080
Like we are setting everything up

03:10:01.080 --> 03:10:03.160
for less lack of communication, lack of understanding.

03:10:03.160 --> 03:10:05.080
How do those feelings of love

03:10:05.080 --> 03:10:07.960
and shared humanness happen?

03:10:07.960 --> 03:10:08.800
They don't, right?

03:10:08.800 --> 03:10:11.680
If you separate people and then we push ourselves

03:10:11.680 --> 03:10:15.080
more and more and more towards reinstating

03:10:15.080 --> 03:10:16.600
the state of entropy that's present

03:10:16.600 --> 03:10:17.960
in the rest of the universe.

03:10:19.160 --> 03:10:21.280
What advice would you give to young people

03:10:23.360 --> 03:10:25.760
that are fighting entropy with all their might?

03:10:26.760 --> 03:10:30.560
So young people and people that are wondering

03:10:30.560 --> 03:10:32.560
how to find their way in life.

03:10:32.560 --> 03:10:34.800
What advice would you give?

03:10:34.800 --> 03:10:35.840
How to have a career?

03:10:35.840 --> 03:10:38.200
How to have a life they can be proud of?

03:10:39.240 --> 03:10:43.760
I think starting off with sort of first principles,

03:10:43.760 --> 03:10:46.160
I'm like, okay, what are my values, right?

03:10:46.160 --> 03:10:47.440
How do I wanna live life?

03:10:47.440 --> 03:10:49.720
Because, you know, I'm in my early fifties

03:10:49.720 --> 03:10:52.240
and when I was a kid, you know, we waited for the,

03:10:52.240 --> 03:10:53.840
the newspaper came in the afternoon

03:10:53.840 --> 03:10:55.760
and then, you know, and then we'd see some,

03:10:55.760 --> 03:10:56.960
okay, what's going on in the world?

03:10:56.960 --> 03:10:57.800
We'd learn something.

03:10:57.800 --> 03:11:00.360
I'd get the West Coast baseball scores, right?

03:11:00.360 --> 03:11:02.520
And learn about, oh, here's what happened

03:11:02.520 --> 03:11:04.160
in different parts of the world.

03:11:04.160 --> 03:11:06.840
And by and large, I and everyone else there,

03:11:06.840 --> 03:11:10.880
adult or child, we're like living in a reality

03:11:10.880 --> 03:11:12.920
that was largely, our conception was largely

03:11:12.920 --> 03:11:14.880
what was around us, right?

03:11:14.880 --> 03:11:17.280
And now, in many ways, it is,

03:11:17.280 --> 03:11:19.040
I'm not saying it's entirely negative, of course,

03:11:19.040 --> 03:11:20.040
that we have more information,

03:11:20.040 --> 03:11:22.640
we can sort of think globally, so to speak, right?

03:11:22.720 --> 03:11:25.440
But the other side of that is so much

03:11:25.440 --> 03:11:29.560
of the world's problems are on us all the time, right?

03:11:29.560 --> 03:11:31.400
Like, here's this awful thing that happened,

03:11:31.400 --> 03:11:33.040
how many awful things happen each day

03:11:33.040 --> 03:11:34.720
and they're right in front of us

03:11:34.720 --> 03:11:37.720
and there's such an immediacy to it all

03:11:37.720 --> 03:11:41.640
that I think it can be like, paralyze us with terror, right?

03:11:41.640 --> 03:11:45.040
And for someone who's young and trying to make their ways,

03:11:45.040 --> 03:11:46.840
like, how do you figure your way out in this world

03:11:46.840 --> 03:11:49.160
that your word isn't even gonna exist, right?

03:11:49.160 --> 03:11:51.320
And then you see how profligate

03:11:51.320 --> 03:11:54.360
the generations before you are, right?

03:11:54.360 --> 03:11:57.400
In so many ways, and there can become,

03:11:57.400 --> 03:12:00.280
I think, a push towards extremes, either nihilism

03:12:00.280 --> 03:12:03.400
or I'm gonna change everything, right?

03:12:03.400 --> 03:12:05.720
And it's like, how about let's start from,

03:12:05.720 --> 03:12:08.600
how do I wanna behave in my own community, right?

03:12:08.600 --> 03:12:09.800
Which starts with like, how do I wanna behave

03:12:09.800 --> 03:12:11.160
in my household, right?

03:12:11.160 --> 03:12:12.400
What kind of neighbor do I wanna be?

03:12:12.400 --> 03:12:14.000
I mean, it might seem like things like that

03:12:14.000 --> 03:12:17.400
are silly or small in comparison to the big things,

03:12:17.400 --> 03:12:18.600
but I don't think they are.

03:12:18.600 --> 03:12:22.120
I think that's how we start building foundations

03:12:22.120 --> 03:12:24.640
that lets us tackle the big things.

03:12:24.640 --> 03:12:27.320
And then I do find myself saying what I'm working with,

03:12:27.320 --> 03:12:29.600
sometimes doing therapy with younger people

03:12:29.600 --> 03:12:33.880
of helping them kind of bring back their thoughts,

03:12:33.880 --> 03:12:37.240
their strivings, their decisions more to themselves

03:12:37.240 --> 03:12:40.440
and living with and around themselves more

03:12:40.440 --> 03:12:44.560
instead of in something that becomes very theoretical

03:12:44.600 --> 03:12:48.600
and therefore very threatening and unnerving.

03:12:48.600 --> 03:12:50.200
So focusing on the people around them,

03:12:50.200 --> 03:12:52.440
taking one small step at a time

03:12:52.440 --> 03:12:56.200
to form deeper connections to build something locally.

03:12:57.080 --> 03:12:58.000
How do I wanna be today?

03:12:58.000 --> 03:12:59.600
If I go into the grocery store

03:12:59.600 --> 03:13:02.000
and the person in front of me drops something,

03:13:02.000 --> 03:13:03.600
I can, I can, I can scow like,

03:13:03.600 --> 03:13:04.640
I'm in a rush, right?

03:13:04.640 --> 03:13:06.520
And I could be like that, right?

03:13:06.520 --> 03:13:07.360
I can be like that.

03:13:07.360 --> 03:13:09.240
I've been that way many, many times in my life, right?

03:13:09.240 --> 03:13:11.400
And it's never done anyone a damn bit of good,

03:13:11.400 --> 03:13:12.640
including me, right?

03:13:12.640 --> 03:13:15.120
Or I can realize like the 10 seconds aren't gonna matter.

03:13:15.120 --> 03:13:17.440
Can I help pick that thing up or just smile?

03:13:17.440 --> 03:13:19.480
These are the seemingly small things

03:13:19.480 --> 03:13:22.600
that I think make the tenor of our lives.

03:13:22.600 --> 03:13:25.760
Yeah, I moved, I think I mentioned to you offline,

03:13:25.760 --> 03:13:30.760
one of the really the main reason I moved to Austin, Texas,

03:13:31.080 --> 03:13:32.480
I just remembered deciding it.

03:13:32.480 --> 03:13:35.520
When I went to Walmart and a lady said,

03:13:37.320 --> 03:13:39.640
you look handsome in that tie

03:13:39.640 --> 03:13:42.040
